VALUES
	('5a68ea2a9c47ff40bdeecb67','3878c69a-9583-44db-93a7-80abdf73c426','jQuery – Prevent Multiple Form Submissions','jquery-prevent-multiple-form-submissions','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"You might think it’d just be a case of:\\n\\n    $(\'form input[type=\\\"submit\\\"]\').attr(\'disabled\',\'disabled\');\\n\\nbut that will prevent the form from submitting because the submit button is now disabled.\\n\\nA better approach is to add a data attribute to the button and use that to determine if the form has already been submitted:\\n\\n    $(\'form\').submit(function() {\\n        // when form is submitted for the first time\\n        // change button text\\n        // and prevent further form submissions\\n        if ($(\'form input[type=\\\"submit\\\"]\').data(\'submitted\') == \'1\') {\\n            return false;\\n        } else {\\n            // I\'ve also added a class and \\n            // changed the value to make it obvious to the \\n            // user that the form is submitting\\n            // but this is entirely optional\\n            // and you can customise this as you wish\\n            $(\'form input[type=\\\"submit\\\"]\')\\n              .attr(\'data-submitted\', \'1\')\\n              .addClass(\'submitting\')\\n              .val(\'Submitting...\');\\n        }\\n    });\\n\\n__DEMO__\\n\\n<p data-height=\\\"268\\\" data-theme-id=\\\"14858\\\" data-slug-hash=\\\"eNpomg\\\" data-default-tab=\\\"result\\\" data-user=\\\"martincarlin87\\\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/eNpomg/\'>jQuery – Prevent Multiple Form Submissions</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\\n<script async src=\\\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\\\"></script>\\n\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>You might think it’d just be a case of:</p>\n<pre><code>$(\'form input[type=&quot;submit&quot;]\').attr(\'disabled\',\'disabled\');\n</code></pre>\n<p>but that will prevent the form from submitting because the submit button is now disabled.</p>\n<p>A better approach is to add a data attribute to the button and use that to determine if the form has already been submitted:</p>\n<pre><code>$(\'form\').submit(function() {\n    // when form is submitted for the first time\n    // change button text\n    // and prevent further form submissions\n    if ($(\'form input[type=&quot;submit&quot;]\').data(\'submitted\') == \'1\') {\n        return false;\n    } else {\n        // I\'ve also added a class and \n        // changed the value to make it obvious to the \n        // user that the form is submitting\n        // but this is entirely optional\n        // and you can customise this as you wish\n        $(\'form input[type=&quot;submit&quot;]\')\n          .attr(\'data-submitted\', \'1\')\n          .addClass(\'submitting\')\n          .val(\'Submitting...\');\n    }\n});\n</code></pre>\n<p><strong>DEMO</strong></p>\n<p data-height=\"268\" data-theme-id=\"14858\" data-slug-hash=\"eNpomg\" data-default-tab=\"result\" data-user=\"martincarlin87\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/eNpomg/\'>jQuery – Prevent Multiple Form Submissions</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\n<script async src=\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\"></script>\n</div>','2','You might think it’d just be a case of:\n\n$(\'form input[type=\"submit\"]\').attr(\'disabled\',\'disabled\');\n\n\nbut that will prevent the form from submitting because the submit button is now\ndisabled.\n\nA better approach is to add a data attribute to the button and use that to\ndetermine if the form has already been submitted:\n\n$(\'form\').submit(function() {\n    // when form is submitted for the first time\n    // change button text\n    // and prevent further form submissions\n    if ($(\'form input[type=\"submit\"]\').data(\'submitted\') == \'1\') {\n        return false;\n    } else {\n        // I\'ve also added a class and \n        // changed the value to make it obvious to the \n        // user that the form is submitting\n        // but this is entirely optional\n        // and you can customise this as you wish\n        $(\'form input[type=\"submit\"]\')\n          .attr(\'data-submitted\', \'1\')\n          .addClass(\'submitting\')\n          .val(\'Submitting...\');\n    }\n});\n\n\nDEMO\n\nSee the Pen jQuery – Prevent Multiple Form Submissions\n[http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/eNpomg/]  by Martin Carlin (\n@martincarlin87 [http://codepen.io/martincarlin87]) on CodePen\n[http://codepen.io].',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2015-05-07 12:24:22','1','2016-02-12 21:24:12','1','2015-05-07 12:31:51','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb6a','f1496f34-0364-4bf5-a5e7-796ecc5e6275','You Can’t JavaScript Under Pressure','you-cant-javascript-under-pressure','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"[You Can’t JavaScript Under Pressure](http://games.usvsth3m.com/javascript-under-pressure/) is a coding game created by us vs th3m which was popular a couple of weeks ago but I thought I’d post my answers incase anyone was stuck and wanted to find the solution.\\n\\n    function doubleInteger(i) {\\n\\n        // i will be an integer. Double it and return it.\\n    \\n        // answer\\n        return i * 2;\\n    }\\n\\n---\\n\\n    function isNumberEven(i) {\\n    \\n        // i will be an integer. Return true if it\'s even, and false if it isn\'t.\\n\\n        // answer\\n        return  (i % 2) == 0\\n\\n    }\\n\\n---\\n\\n    function getFileExtension(i) {\\n    \\n        // i will be a string, but it may not have a file extension.\\n        // return the file extension (with no period)\\n        // if it has one, otherwise false\\n\\n        // answer (assuming filenames don\'t have dots in them)\\n        if (i.indexOf(\'.\') != -1) {\\n            var extension = i.split(\'.\').pop();\\n            return extension;\\n        } else {\\n            return false;\\n        } \\n    }\\n\\n---\\n\\n    function longestString(i) {\\n    \\n        // i will be an array.\\n        // return the longest string in the array\\n\\n        // answer\\n        var length = 0;\\n        var longest;\\n\\n        for (var count = 0; count < i.length; count++) {\\n            if (i[count].length > length && typeof i[count] == \'string\') {\\n                length = i[count].length;\\n                longest = i[count];\\n            }      \\n        } \\n        return longest;\\n    }\\n\\n---\\n\\n    function arraySum(i) {\\n    \\n        // i will be an array, containing integers, strings\\n        // and/or arrays like itself.\\n        // Sum all the integers you find, anywhere in the nest of arrays.\\n\\n        var total = 0;\\n\\n        // answer\\n        for (var count = 0; count < i.length; count++) {\\n            if (typeof i[count] === \'number\') {\\n                total += i[count];\\n            } else if (Array.isArray(i[count])) {\\n                total += arraySum(i[count]);\\n            }\\n\\n        }\\n        return total;\\n    }\\n\\n\\n\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p><a href=\"http://games.usvsth3m.com/javascript-under-pressure/\">You Can’t JavaScript Under Pressure</a> is a coding game created by us vs th3m which was popular a couple of weeks ago but I thought I’d post my answers incase anyone was stuck and wanted to find the solution.</p>\n<pre><code>function doubleInteger(i) {\n\n    // i will be an integer. Double it and return it.\n\n    // answer\n    return i * 2;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n<pre><code>function isNumberEven(i) {\n\n    // i will be an integer. Return true if it\'s even, and false if it isn\'t.\n\n    // answer\n    return  (i % 2) == 0\n\n}\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n<pre><code>function getFileExtension(i) {\n\n    // i will be a string, but it may not have a file extension.\n    // return the file extension (with no period)\n    // if it has one, otherwise false\n\n    // answer (assuming filenames don\'t have dots in them)\n    if (i.indexOf(\'.\') != -1) {\n        var extension = i.split(\'.\').pop();\n        return extension;\n    } else {\n        return false;\n    } \n}\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n<pre><code>function longestString(i) {\n\n    // i will be an array.\n    // return the longest string in the array\n\n    // answer\n    var length = 0;\n    var longest;\n\n    for (var count = 0; count &lt; i.length; count++) {\n        if (i[count].length &gt; length &amp;&amp; typeof i[count] == \'string\') {\n            length = i[count].length;\n            longest = i[count];\n        }      \n    } \n    return longest;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<hr>\n<pre><code>function arraySum(i) {\n\n    // i will be an array, containing integers, strings\n    // and/or arrays like itself.\n    // Sum all the integers you find, anywhere in the nest of arrays.\n\n    var total = 0;\n\n    // answer\n    for (var count = 0; count &lt; i.length; count++) {\n        if (typeof i[count] === \'number\') {\n            total += i[count];\n        } else if (Array.isArray(i[count])) {\n            total += arraySum(i[count]);\n        }\n\n    }\n    return total;\n}\n</code></pre>\n</div>','3','You Can’t JavaScript Under Pressure\n[http://games.usvsth3m.com/javascript-under-pressure/]  is a coding game created\nby us vs th3m which was popular a couple of weeks ago but I thought I’d post my\nanswers incase anyone was stuck and wanted to find the solution.\n\nfunction doubleInteger(i) {\n\n    // i will be an integer. Double it and return it.\n\n    // answer\n    return i * 2;\n}\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nfunction isNumberEven(i) {\n\n    // i will be an integer. Return true if it\'s even, and false if it isn\'t.\n\n    // answer\n    return  (i % 2) == 0\n\n}\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nfunction getFileExtension(i) {\n\n    // i will be a string, but it may not have a file extension.\n    // return the file extension (with no period)\n    // if it has one, otherwise false\n\n    // answer (assuming filenames don\'t have dots in them)\n    if (i.indexOf(\'.\') != -1) {\n        var extension = i.split(\'.\').pop();\n        return extension;\n    } else {\n        return false;\n    } \n}\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nfunction longestString(i) {\n\n    // i will be an array.\n    // return the longest string in the array\n\n    // answer\n    var length = 0;\n    var longest;\n\n    for (var count = 0; count < i.length; count++) {\n        if (i[count].length > length && typeof i[count] == \'string\') {\n            length = i[count].length;\n            longest = i[count];\n        }      \n    } \n    return longest;\n}\n\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nfunction arraySum(i) {\n\n    // i will be an array, containing integers, strings\n    // and/or arrays like itself.\n    // Sum all the integers you find, anywhere in the nest of arrays.\n\n    var total = 0;\n\n    // answer\n    for (var count = 0; count < i.length; count++) {\n        if (typeof i[count] === \'number\') {\n            total += i[count];\n        } else if (Array.isArray(i[count])) {\n            total += arraySum(i[count]);\n        }\n\n    }\n    return total;\n}',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2015-05-07 12:40:27','1','2016-02-12 21:23:37','1','2015-05-07 12:48:49','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb6c','cc4492f9-6cc5-423c-b504-d049e6f0aa0d','About','about','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"<div class=\\\"content has-text-centered\\\">\\n  <a href=\\\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/634120/martincarlin87\\\">\\n<img src=\\\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/flair/634120.png\\\" width=\\\"208\\\" height=\\\"58\\\" alt=\\\"profile for martincarlin87 at Stack Overflow, Q&amp;A for professional and enthusiast programmers\\\" title=\\\"profile for martincarlin87 at Stack Overflow, Q&amp;A for professional and enthusiast programmers\\\"></a>\\n</div>\\n\\nHello, my name is Martin Carlin and I am a Web Developer and bass player from Motherwell in Scotland.\\n\\nI would describe myself as an all-round, full-stack web developer specialising in PHP, Laravel, MySQL, JavaScript / jQuery, CSS and various APIs I\'ve used over the years.\\n\\nI am particularly keen on Laravel and would love to continue using it in any future roles.\\n\\nI enjoy the problem solving aspects of web development and learning new technologies, as well as creating nice UIs with pleasant user experiences, especially when it\'s an abstraction to a particularly challenging feature.\\n\\nIn my spare time I play bass in a four-piece wedding band based in Motherwell called [4Play](https://www.4playtheband.co.uk) and have been doing so for the last ten years or so.\\n\\nYou can probably tell I\'m a bit of a Marvel fan from the header image(s) too, I always struggled to come up with an image to show at the top of my personal websites and think it looks bare without one, so I think I\'ve finally found something that works for me.\\n\\nIn addition to all of the above, I also have a pet Siberian Husky called Silver, shown here looking particularly vicious whilst dive-bombing some snow a couple of years ago:\\n\\n<img src=\\\"/content/images/2016/02/silver.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"Silver\\\" style=\\\"max-height: 350px; margin: 20px auto; display: block;\\\">\\n\\n<div class=\\\"content has-text-centered\\\">\\n  <a href=\\\"https://gamercards.exophase.com/xbox/user/martincarlin87/\\\"><img src=\\\"https://card.exophase.com/1/978981.png\\\"></a>\\n</div>\\n\\nThis Ghost theme was developed using the [Bulma](http://bulma.io/) Flexbox framework and is available on [GitHub](https://github.com/martincarlin87/carlin).\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><div class=\"content has-text-centered\">\n  <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/634120/martincarlin87\">\n<img src=\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/flair/634120.png\" width=\"208\" height=\"58\" alt=\"profile for martincarlin87 at Stack Overflow, Q&amp;A for professional and enthusiast programmers\" title=\"profile for martincarlin87 at Stack Overflow, Q&amp;A for professional and enthusiast programmers\"></a>\n</div>\n<p>Hello, my name is Martin Carlin and I am a Web Developer and bass player from Motherwell in Scotland.</p>\n<p>I would describe myself as an all-round, full-stack web developer specialising in PHP, Laravel, MySQL, JavaScript / jQuery, CSS and various APIs I\'ve used over the years.</p>\n<p>I am particularly keen on Laravel and would love to continue using it in any future roles.</p>\n<p>I enjoy the problem solving aspects of web development and learning new technologies, as well as creating nice UIs with pleasant user experiences, especially when it\'s an abstraction to a particularly challenging feature.</p>\n<p>In my spare time I play bass in a four-piece wedding band based in Motherwell called <a href=\"https://www.4playtheband.co.uk\">4Play</a> and have been doing so for the last ten years or so.</p>\n<p>You can probably tell I\'m a bit of a Marvel fan from the header image(s) too, I always struggled to come up with an image to show at the top of my personal websites and think it looks bare without one, so I think I\'ve finally found something that works for me.</p>\n<p>In addition to all of the above, I also have a pet Siberian Husky called Silver, shown here looking particularly vicious whilst dive-bombing some snow a couple of years ago:</p>\n<img src=\"/content/images/2016/02/silver.jpg\" alt=\"Silver\" style=\"max-height: 350px; margin: 20px auto; display: block;\">\n<div class=\"content has-text-centered\">\n  <a href=\"https://gamercards.exophase.com/xbox/user/martincarlin87/\"><img src=\"https://card.exophase.com/1/978981.png\"></a>\n</div>\n<p>This Ghost theme was developed using the <a href=\"http://bulma.io/\">Bulma</a> Flexbox framework and is available on <a href=\"https://github.com/martincarlin87/carlin\">GitHub</a>.</p>\n</div>','4','[https://stackoverflow.com/users/634120/martincarlin87]Hello, my name is Martin\nCarlin and I am a Web Developer and bass player from Motherwell in Scotland.\n\nI would describe myself as an all-round, full-stack web developer specialising\nin PHP, Laravel, MySQL, JavaScript / jQuery, CSS and various APIs I\'ve used over\nthe years.\n\nI am particularly keen on Laravel and would love to continue using it in any\nfuture roles.\n\nI enjoy the problem solving aspects of web development and learning new\ntechnologies, as well as creating nice UIs with pleasant user experiences,\nespecially when it\'s an abstraction to a particularly challenging feature.\n\nIn my spare time I play bass in a four-piece wedding band based in Motherwell\ncalled 4Play [https://www.4playtheband.co.uk]  and have been doing so for the\nlast ten years or so.\n\nYou can probably tell I\'m a bit of a Marvel fan from the header image(s) too, I\nalways struggled to come up with an image to show at the top of my personal\nwebsites and think it looks bare without one, so I think I\'ve finally found\nsomething that works for me.\n\nIn addition to all of the above, I also have a pet Siberian Husky called Silver,\nshown here looking particularly vicious whilst dive-bombing some snow a couple\nof years ago:\n\n[https://gamercards.exophase.com/xbox/user/martincarlin87/]This Ghost theme was\ndeveloped using the Bulma [http://bulma.io/]  Flexbox framework and is available\non GitHub [https://github.com/martincarlin87/carlin].',NULL,0,1,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2015-05-07 13:12:34','1','2018-03-15 14:43:46','1','2015-05-07 13:12:59','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb6e','31e74392-34cd-4c46-beec-05beaf6d7817','Hi There!','home','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"I am Martin Carlin, a web developer from Motherwell and bass player for [4Play](https://www.4playtheband.co.uk).\\n\\n<div id=\\\"instafeed\\\" class=\\\"container\\\"></div>\\n\\n<hr>\\n\\n<h3 class=\\\"title is-3 has-text-centered\\\">Side Projects</h3>  \\n\\nSome are for personal development to learn something new and others are for people and small businesses that I\'ve been helping out.\\n\\n* [Chris Scott Music Website](https://www.chrisscottmusic.co.uk/) - website for singer/songwrite Chris Scott.\\n\\n* [Vauxhall Parts UK Website](http://www.vauxhallpartsuk.com/) - redesign of existing website.\\n\\n* [Sense Intimates Website](https://www.senseintimates.co.uk) - e-commerce website for a friend launching a new lingerie business.\\n\\n* [Mr Karma Productions Website](https://www.mrkarmaproductions.co.uk) - video production business run by a friend.\\n\\n* [Elite Contracts Ltd Website](http://elitecontractsltd.co.uk) - business run by a friend who are Data and Electrical Cable Installers.\\n\\n* [Lothian Auto Parts Website](https://lothianautoparts.uk) - friend who needed a website to advertise their business and pull their eBay listings.\\n\\n* [Lothian Auto Parts eBay Shop](http://stores.ebay.co.uk/lothianautoparts01506811367/) - custom designed eBay store.\\n\\n* [Rails 4 Currency Converter](http://freeagent.4playtheband.co.uk/) - pre-interview technical test issued by FreeAgent, but getting messy now since the chart shows the data for every day.\\n\\n* [Fiona Shiel Graphic Designer](https://fionashiel.co.uk/) - website for Fiona Shiel.\\n\\n* [4Play Wedding Band](https://4playtheband.co.uk/) - website for my own band.\\n\\n* [The Hustle Wedding Band](https://www.thehustleweddingband.co.uk/) - website for my friend\'s band.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>I am Martin Carlin, a web developer from Motherwell and bass player for <a href=\"https://www.4playtheband.co.uk\">4Play</a>.</p>\n<div id=\"instafeed\" class=\"container\"></div>\n<hr>\n<h3 class=\"title is-3 has-text-centered\">Side Projects</h3>  \n<p>Some are for personal development to learn something new and others are for people and small businesses that I\'ve been helping out.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.chrisscottmusic.co.uk/\">Chris Scott Music Website</a> - website for singer/songwrite Chris Scott.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.vauxhallpartsuk.com/\">Vauxhall Parts UK Website</a> - redesign of existing website.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.senseintimates.co.uk\">Sense Intimates Website</a> - e-commerce website for a friend launching a new lingerie business.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.mrkarmaproductions.co.uk\">Mr Karma Productions Website</a> - video production business run by a friend.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"http://elitecontractsltd.co.uk\">Elite Contracts Ltd Website</a> - business run by a friend who are Data and Electrical Cable Installers.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"https://lothianautoparts.uk\">Lothian Auto Parts Website</a> - friend who needed a website to advertise their business and pull their eBay listings.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"http://stores.ebay.co.uk/lothianautoparts01506811367/\">Lothian Auto Parts eBay Shop</a> - custom designed eBay store.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"http://freeagent.4playtheband.co.uk/\">Rails 4 Currency Converter</a> - pre-interview technical test issued by FreeAgent, but getting messy now since the chart shows the data for every day.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"https://fionashiel.co.uk/\">Fiona Shiel Graphic Designer</a> - website for Fiona Shiel.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"https://4playtheband.co.uk/\">4Play Wedding Band</a> - website for my own band.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.thehustleweddingband.co.uk/\">The Hustle Wedding Band</a> - website for my friend\'s band.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>','6','I am Martin Carlin, a web developer from Motherwell and bass player for 4Play\n[https://www.4playtheband.co.uk].\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nSide Projects\nSome are for personal development to learn something new and others are for\npeople and small businesses that I\'ve been helping out.\n\n * Chris Scott Music Website [https://www.chrisscottmusic.co.uk/]  - website for\n   singer/songwrite Chris Scott.\n   \n   \n * Vauxhall Parts UK Website [http://www.vauxhallpartsuk.com/]  - redesign of\n   existing website.\n   \n   \n * Sense Intimates Website [https://www.senseintimates.co.uk]  - e-commerce\n   website for a friend launching a new lingerie business.\n   \n   \n * Mr Karma Productions Website [https://www.mrkarmaproductions.co.uk]  - video\n   production business run by a friend.\n   \n   \n * Elite Contracts Ltd Website [http://elitecontractsltd.co.uk]  - business run\n   by a friend who are Data and Electrical Cable Installers.\n   \n   \n * Lothian Auto Parts Website [https://lothianautoparts.uk]  - friend who needed\n   a website to advertise their business and pull their eBay listings.\n   \n   \n * Lothian Auto Parts eBay Shop\n   [http://stores.ebay.co.uk/lothianautoparts01506811367/]  - custom designed\n   eBay store.\n   \n   \n * Rails 4 Currency Converter [http://freeagent.4playtheband.co.uk/]  -\n   pre-interview technical test issued by FreeAgent, but getting messy now since\n   the chart shows the data for every day.\n   \n   \n * Fiona Shiel Graphic Designer [https://fionashiel.co.uk/]  - website for Fiona\n   Shiel.\n   \n   \n * 4Play Wedding Band [https://4playtheband.co.uk/]  - website for my own band.\n   \n   \n * The Hustle Wedding Band [https://www.thehustleweddingband.co.uk/]  - website\n   for my friend\'s band.',NULL,0,1,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-09 19:47:51','1','2018-03-30 16:25:34','1','2016-02-09 19:48:20','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb70','6271c727-c6a2-4598-ab63-978d7538e94a','Contact','contact','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"Please feel free to contact me if you have any questions about any of my blog posts or anything else.\\n\\nYou can reach me using the contact form, or if you prefer, you can email me at martin[at]martincarlin.uk or get in touch via [twitter](https://twitter.com/martincarlin87).\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>Please feel free to contact me if you have any questions about any of my blog posts or anything else.</p>\n<p>You can reach me using the contact form, or if you prefer, you can email me at martin[at]martincarlin.uk or get in touch via <a href=\"https://twitter.com/martincarlin87\">twitter</a>.</p>\n</div>','8','Please feel free to contact me if you have any questions about any of my blog\nposts or anything else.\n\nYou can reach me using the contact form, or if you prefer, you can email me at\nmartin[at]martincarlin.uk or get in touch via twitter\n[https://twitter.com/martincarlin87].',NULL,0,1,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-09 19:50:50','1','2018-03-15 14:45:12','1','2016-02-09 19:51:01','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb72','1857e1c0-4484-4eac-85b1-34c7a9b5ccff','Blog','blog','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"These are all of my blog posts, where possible/applicable, I\'ll include an embedded CodePen demo or a gist, I hope you find them useful.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>These are all of my blog posts, where possible/applicable, I\'ll include an embedded CodePen demo or a gist, I hope you find them useful.</p>\n</div>','12','These are all of my blog posts, where possible/applicable, I\'ll include an\nembedded CodePen demo or a gist, I hope you find them useful.',NULL,0,1,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-10 09:53:32','1','2018-03-15 14:45:44','1','2016-02-10 09:53:32','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb74','496dd26d-ed1d-45d6-9bd3-9cdbb4250340','CV & Skills','cv-and-skills','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"You can download my CV [here](/files/cv.pdf).\\n\\n**N.B.** My CV was created using Sketch which is designed for screen layouts, so if you try and print the CV it will not be split nicely between pages.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>You can download my CV <a href=\"/files/cv.pdf\">here</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>N.B.</strong> My CV was created using Sketch which is designed for screen layouts, so if you try and print the CV it will not be split nicely between pages.</p>\n</div>','13','You can download my CV here [/files/cv.pdf].\n\nN.B.  My CV was created using Sketch which is designed for screen layouts, so if\nyou try and print the CV it will not be split nicely between pages.',NULL,0,1,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-10 11:20:23','1','2018-03-15 14:44:28','1','2016-02-10 11:20:23','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb76','bcf891da-66d3-40bc-a5a1-016b6d5f2b74','Random Coloured Responsive Flexbox Nav','random-coloured-responsive-flexbox-nav','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"<p data-height=\\\"266\\\" data-theme-id=\\\"14858\\\" data-slug-hash=\\\"NxzqBX\\\" data-default-tab=\\\"result\\\" data-user=\\\"martincarlin87\\\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/NxzqBX/\'>Random Coloured Responsive Flexbox Nav</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\\n<script async src=\\\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\\\"></script>\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p data-height=\"266\" data-theme-id=\"14858\" data-slug-hash=\"NxzqBX\" data-default-tab=\"result\" data-user=\"martincarlin87\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/NxzqBX/\'>Random Coloured Responsive Flexbox Nav</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\n<script async src=\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\"></script></div>','14','See the Pen Random Coloured Responsive Flexbox Nav\n[http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/NxzqBX/]  by Martin Carlin (\n@martincarlin87 [http://codepen.io/martincarlin87]) on CodePen\n[http://codepen.io].',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-10 12:55:06','1','2016-02-12 21:25:22','1','2016-02-10 12:55:30','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb7b','1125a0e1-4e0c-40d1-a700-7245b055b53c','Bootstrap Markdown Solution for Fixed Containers','untitled','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"<p data-height=\\\"266\\\" data-theme-id=\\\"14858\\\" data-slug-hash=\\\"Qbgjge\\\" data-default-tab=\\\"result\\\" data-user=\\\"martincarlin87\\\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/Qbgjge/\'>Bootstrap Markdown Solution for Fixed Containers</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\\n<script async src=\\\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\\\"></script>\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p data-height=\"266\" data-theme-id=\"14858\" data-slug-hash=\"Qbgjge\" data-default-tab=\"result\" data-user=\"martincarlin87\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/Qbgjge/\'>Bootstrap Markdown Solution for Fixed Containers</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\n<script async src=\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\"></script></div>','15','See the Pen Bootstrap Markdown Solution for Fixed Containers\n[http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/Qbgjge/]  by Martin Carlin (\n@martincarlin87 [http://codepen.io/martincarlin87]) on CodePen\n[http://codepen.io].',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-10 12:58:12','1','2016-02-12 21:25:05','1','2016-02-10 12:58:00','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb80','263a82f6-1149-44ab-86a8-c9776dc2a89d','Bootstrap X-editable On-Change Event','bootstrap-x-editable-on-change-event','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"<p data-height=\\\"266\\\" data-theme-id=\\\"14858\\\" data-slug-hash=\\\"aOWoXB\\\" data-default-tab=\\\"result\\\" data-user=\\\"martincarlin87\\\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/aOWoXB/\'>Bootstrap X-editable On-Change Event</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\\n<script async src=\\\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\\\"></script>\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p data-height=\"266\" data-theme-id=\"14858\" data-slug-hash=\"aOWoXB\" data-default-tab=\"result\" data-user=\"martincarlin87\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/aOWoXB/\'>Bootstrap X-editable On-Change Event</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\n<script async src=\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\"></script></div>','16','See the Pen Bootstrap X-editable On-Change Event\n[http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/aOWoXB/]  by Martin Carlin (\n@martincarlin87 [http://codepen.io/martincarlin87]) on CodePen\n[http://codepen.io].',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-10 12:59:33','1','2016-02-12 21:24:43','1','2016-02-10 12:59:37','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb85','33e8080a-fcb1-49b1-8ec0-655a5165882d','How To Use Capistrano 3 for Ghost Theme Deployment','how-to-use-capistrano-3-for-ghost-theme-deployment','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"To install a theme on Ghost, it\'s easy enough to do so from a git repo by `cd`-ing to the `content` directory and doing:\\n\\n    git clone repo_url.git\\n    // change permissions, restart ghost etc.\\n\\nWhat if there was another way where you didn\'t have to manually ssh to the (production) server every time there was an update?\\n\\nThis is something I wanted to do whilst developing my own personal Ghost theme - initially I had a local setup with Vagrant and VirtualBox but the time came when I wanted to actually deploy.\\n\\nThe problems I faced when trying to configure Capistrano were out-of-date blog posts that were written about Capistrano 2, or weren\'t quite suitable as they were geared towards the deployment of full projects rather than a single directory buried within the bowels of an existing app, which admittedly, is the main use case for Capistrano.\\n\\nTo begin, you need to `cd` to the directory that contains your theme on your local machine.\\n\\n    cd theme_directory\\n\\nThen, we need to install the Capistrano gem, so you will need Ruby installed, which is probably the case if you\'re on Mac OS X.\\n\\n    gem install capistrano\\n\\nOnce the gem is installed, we need to Capify our project.\\n\\n    cap install\\n\\nThis sets up all the files that Capistrano needs in order to function.\\n\\nNow we need to edit the `config/deploy.rb` file:\\n\\n    # config valid only for current version of Capistrano\\n    lock \'3.4.0\'\\n\\n    set :application, \'theme_name\'\\n    set :repo_url, \'repo_url.git\'\\n\\n    set :deploy_to, \'/var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\\n\\n    set :user, \'deploy_user\'\\n\\n    namespace :deploy do\\n      desc \'Restart application\'\\n      task :restart do\\n        on roles(:web), in: :sequence, wait: 5 do \\n\\n          # here we are setting up the symlinks to point from the current release directory to the top level of the theme directory\\n          execute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/REVISION /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/REVISION\'\\n            \\n          execute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/* /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\\n          \\n          execute \'sudo chown -R ghost_user:ghost_user /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\\n          \\n          # restart the forever process (or pm2, ghost service etc.)\\n          execute \'sudo forever restart /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/index.js\'\\n        end\\n      end\\n\\n      after :publishing, \'deploy:restart\'\\n    end\\n\\nOnce that\'s done, edit the `config/deploy/production.rb` file with the following:\\n\\n    server \'your_server_url\', user: \'deploy_user\', roles: %w{web app}\\n\\n\\nFinally, from your project directory, run\\n\\n    cap production deploy\\n\\nTo enable more environments like staging, just edit the `staging.rb` file as you did with production.\\n\\nAll the output can be pretty off-putting, but don\'t worry, if configured properly then your theme should deploy without any hitches.\\n\\nIf you encounter any issues, you can re-run the command w0th the `--trace option` (`cap production deploy --trace`).\\n\\nSome things to watch out for is to make sure that the `deploy_user` you are using is added to the `/etc/sudoers` file and has shell access. I also highly recommend you setup ssh keys to make things much, much easier.\\n\\nIf you are not familiar with Capistrano, the `current` directory is a symlink to the latest release in the `releases` directory which also contains the last x number of releases (the last five are kept by default, including the most recent but this can be changed in your `deploy.rb` file.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>To install a theme on Ghost, it\'s easy enough to do so from a git repo by <code>cd</code>-ing to the <code>content</code> directory and doing:</p>\n<pre><code>git clone repo_url.git\n// change permissions, restart ghost etc.\n</code></pre>\n<p>What if there was another way where you didn\'t have to manually ssh to the (production) server every time there was an update?</p>\n<p>This is something I wanted to do whilst developing my own personal Ghost theme - initially I had a local setup with Vagrant and VirtualBox but the time came when I wanted to actually deploy.</p>\n<p>The problems I faced when trying to configure Capistrano were out-of-date blog posts that were written about Capistrano 2, or weren\'t quite suitable as they were geared towards the deployment of full projects rather than a single directory buried within the bowels of an existing app, which admittedly, is the main use case for Capistrano.</p>\n<p>To begin, you need to <code>cd</code> to the directory that contains your theme on your local machine.</p>\n<pre><code>cd theme_directory\n</code></pre>\n<p>Then, we need to install the Capistrano gem, so you will need Ruby installed, which is probably the case if you\'re on Mac OS X.</p>\n<pre><code>gem install capistrano\n</code></pre>\n<p>Once the gem is installed, we need to Capify our project.</p>\n<pre><code>cap install\n</code></pre>\n<p>This sets up all the files that Capistrano needs in order to function.</p>\n<p>Now we need to edit the <code>config/deploy.rb</code> file:</p>\n<pre><code># config valid only for current version of Capistrano\nlock \'3.4.0\'\n\nset :application, \'theme_name\'\nset :repo_url, \'repo_url.git\'\n\nset :deploy_to, \'/var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n\nset :user, \'deploy_user\'\n\nnamespace :deploy do\n  desc \'Restart application\'\n  task :restart do\n    on roles(:web), in: :sequence, wait: 5 do \n\n      # here we are setting up the symlinks to point from the current release directory to the top level of the theme directory\n      execute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/REVISION /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/REVISION\'\n        \n      execute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/* /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n      \n      execute \'sudo chown -R ghost_user:ghost_user /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n      \n      # restart the forever process (or pm2, ghost service etc.)\n      execute \'sudo forever restart /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/index.js\'\n    end\n  end\n\n  after :publishing, \'deploy:restart\'\nend\n</code></pre>\n<p>Once that\'s done, edit the <code>config/deploy/production.rb</code> file with the following:</p>\n<pre><code>server \'your_server_url\', user: \'deploy_user\', roles: %w{web app}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Finally, from your project directory, run</p>\n<pre><code>cap production deploy\n</code></pre>\n<p>To enable more environments like staging, just edit the <code>staging.rb</code> file as you did with production.</p>\n<p>All the output can be pretty off-putting, but don\'t worry, if configured properly then your theme should deploy without any hitches.</p>\n<p>If you encounter any issues, you can re-run the command w0th the <code>--trace option</code> (<code>cap production deploy --trace</code>).</p>\n<p>Some things to watch out for is to make sure that the <code>deploy_user</code> you are using is added to the <code>/etc/sudoers</code> file and has shell access. I also highly recommend you setup ssh keys to make things much, much easier.</p>\n<p>If you are not familiar with Capistrano, the <code>current</code> directory is a symlink to the latest release in the <code>releases</code> directory which also contains the last x number of releases (the last five are kept by default, including the most recent but this can be changed in your <code>deploy.rb</code> file.</p>\n</div>','17','To install a theme on Ghost, it\'s easy enough to do so from a git repo by cd-ing\nto the content  directory and doing:\n\ngit clone repo_url.git\n// change permissions, restart ghost etc.\n\n\nWhat if there was another way where you didn\'t have to manually ssh to the\n(production) server every time there was an update?\n\nThis is something I wanted to do whilst developing my own personal Ghost theme -\ninitially I had a local setup with Vagrant and VirtualBox but the time came when\nI wanted to actually deploy.\n\nThe problems I faced when trying to configure Capistrano were out-of-date blog\nposts that were written about Capistrano 2, or weren\'t quite suitable as they\nwere geared towards the deployment of full projects rather than a single\ndirectory buried within the bowels of an existing app, which admittedly, is the\nmain use case for Capistrano.\n\nTo begin, you need to cd  to the directory that contains your theme on your\nlocal machine.\n\ncd theme_directory\n\n\nThen, we need to install the Capistrano gem, so you will need Ruby installed,\nwhich is probably the case if you\'re on Mac OS X.\n\ngem install capistrano\n\n\nOnce the gem is installed, we need to Capify our project.\n\ncap install\n\n\nThis sets up all the files that Capistrano needs in order to function.\n\nNow we need to edit the config/deploy.rb  file:\n\n# config valid only for current version of Capistrano\nlock \'3.4.0\'\n\nset :application, \'theme_name\'\nset :repo_url, \'repo_url.git\'\n\nset :deploy_to, \'/var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n\nset :user, \'deploy_user\'\n\nnamespace :deploy do\n  desc \'Restart application\'\n  task :restart do\n    on roles(:web), in: :sequence, wait: 5 do \n\n      # here we are setting up the symlinks to point from the current release directory to the top level of the theme directory\n      execute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/REVISION /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/REVISION\'\n        \n      execute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/* /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n      \n      execute \'sudo chown -R ghost_user:ghost_user /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n      \n      # restart the forever process (or pm2, ghost service etc.)\n      execute \'sudo forever restart /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/index.js\'\n    end\n  end\n\n  after :publishing, \'deploy:restart\'\nend\n\n\nOnce that\'s done, edit the config/deploy/production.rb  file with the following:\n\nserver \'your_server_url\', user: \'deploy_user\', roles: %w{web app}\n\n\nFinally, from your project directory, run\n\ncap production deploy\n\n\nTo enable more environments like staging, just edit the staging.rb  file as you\ndid with production.\n\nAll the output can be pretty off-putting, but don\'t worry, if configured\nproperly then your theme should deploy without any hitches.\n\nIf you encounter any issues, you can re-run the command w0th the --trace option \n(cap production deploy --trace).\n\nSome things to watch out for is to make sure that the deploy_user  you are using\nis added to the /etc/sudoers  file and has shell access. I also highly recommend\nyou setup ssh keys to make things much, much easier.\n\nIf you are not familiar with Capistrano, the current  directory is a symlink to\nthe latest release in the releases  directory which also contains the last x\nnumber of releases (the last five are kept by default, including the most recent\nbut this can be changed in your deploy.rb  file.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-12 21:44:21','1','2016-02-14 14:56:39','1','2016-02-14 14:56:39','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb8b','056f407e-56b2-43f4-baf4-1e58e60992b4','Bulma CSS Framework - Add Functionality to Dismiss Notifications','bulma-css-framework-add-functionality-to-dismiss-notifications','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"As you may know, I am using the [Bulma](http://bulma.io/) flexbox css framework for my personal Ghost theme.\\n\\nAs part of the framework, there are notifications and the framework also provides the ability to include a delete button for the notification, but it is completely static and doesn\'t do anything - yet.\\n\\n\\n\\nI also had to add some CSS to fix the button for the notification:\\n\\n    .notification > button.delete {\\n      border: none;\\n    } \\n\\nwhich is strange as it seems fine on the Bulma site.\\n\\nIn addition to this, I added a new modifier class in the naming convention of the existing classes:\\n\\n    .is-hidden {\\n      display: none;\\n    }\\n\\nThis class is then applied to the notification when the delete button is clicked.\\n\\nTo achieve that in jQuery, you can simply use this:\\n\\n    $(document).on(\'click\', \'.notification > button.delete\', function() {\\n        $(this).parent().addClass(\'is-hidden\');\\n        return false;\\n    });\\n\\nYou could optionally remove the element from the DOM completely by chaining the `.remove()` method, e.g.\\n\\n    $(this).parent().addClass(\'is-hidden\').remove();\\n\\n<p data-height=\\\"266\\\" data-theme-id=\\\"14858\\\" data-slug-hash=\\\"yewgNy\\\" data-default-tab=\\\"result\\\" data-user=\\\"martincarlin87\\\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/yewgNy/\'>Bulma CSS Framework - Add Functionality to Dismiss Notifications</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\\n<script async src=\\\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\\\"></script>\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>As you may know, I am using the <a href=\"http://bulma.io/\">Bulma</a> flexbox css framework for my personal Ghost theme.</p>\n<p>As part of the framework, there are notifications and the framework also provides the ability to include a delete button for the notification, but it is completely static and doesn\'t do anything - yet.</p>\n<p>I also had to add some CSS to fix the button for the notification:</p>\n<pre><code>.notification &gt; button.delete {\n  border: none;\n} \n</code></pre>\n<p>which is strange as it seems fine on the Bulma site.</p>\n<p>In addition to this, I added a new modifier class in the naming convention of the existing classes:</p>\n<pre><code>.is-hidden {\n  display: none;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>This class is then applied to the notification when the delete button is clicked.</p>\n<p>To achieve that in jQuery, you can simply use this:</p>\n<pre><code>$(document).on(\'click\', \'.notification &gt; button.delete\', function() {\n    $(this).parent().addClass(\'is-hidden\');\n    return false;\n});\n</code></pre>\n<p>You could optionally remove the element from the DOM completely by chaining the <code>.remove()</code> method, e.g.</p>\n<pre><code>$(this).parent().addClass(\'is-hidden\').remove();\n</code></pre>\n<p data-height=\"266\" data-theme-id=\"14858\" data-slug-hash=\"yewgNy\" data-default-tab=\"result\" data-user=\"martincarlin87\" class=\'codepen\'>See the Pen <a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/yewgNy/\'>Bulma CSS Framework - Add Functionality to Dismiss Notifications</a> by Martin Carlin (<a href=\'http://codepen.io/martincarlin87\'>@martincarlin87</a>) on <a href=\'http://codepen.io\'>CodePen</a>.</p>\n<script async src=\"//assets.codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js\"></script></div>','18','As you may know, I am using the Bulma [http://bulma.io/]  flexbox css framework\nfor my personal Ghost theme.\n\nAs part of the framework, there are notifications and the framework also\nprovides the ability to include a delete button for the notification, but it is\ncompletely static and doesn\'t do anything - yet.\n\nI also had to add some CSS to fix the button for the notification:\n\n.notification > button.delete {\n  border: none;\n} \n\n\nwhich is strange as it seems fine on the Bulma site.\n\nIn addition to this, I added a new modifier class in the naming convention of\nthe existing classes:\n\n.is-hidden {\n  display: none;\n}\n\n\nThis class is then applied to the notification when the delete button is\nclicked.\n\nTo achieve that in jQuery, you can simply use this:\n\n$(document).on(\'click\', \'.notification > button.delete\', function() {\n    $(this).parent().addClass(\'is-hidden\');\n    return false;\n});\n\n\nYou could optionally remove the element from the DOM completely by chaining the \n.remove()  method, e.g.\n\n$(this).parent().addClass(\'is-hidden\').remove();\n\n\nSee the Pen Bulma CSS Framework - Add Functionality to Dismiss Notifications\n[http://codepen.io/martincarlin87/pen/yewgNy/]  by Martin Carlin (\n@martincarlin87 [http://codepen.io/martincarlin87]) on CodePen\n[http://codepen.io].',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-15 13:01:15','1','2016-02-15 13:19:10','1','2016-02-15 13:19:10','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb91','baf5d9e4-ca17-4bb8-b4a8-147f0a4550a4','How to Use SASS with Your Ghost Theme','how-to-use-sass-with-your-ghost-theme','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"This post is a follow-on from [How to Use Capistrano 3 for Ghost Theme Deployment](https://martincarlin.uk/2016/02/14/how-to-use-capistrano-3-for-ghost-theme-deployment/), so please read that first.\\n\\nThe aim of this post is to introduce SASS to the workflow instead of vanilla CSS.\\n\\nI followed this excellent blog post [here](https://www.ghostforbeginners.com/using-sass-with-ghost/) but I will describe what specific changes I made to my local project.\\n\\nFirst off, as the post points out, you need to install the SASS gem both to your local machine and your production server.\\n\\n    gem install sass\\n\\nWhen installing on production, the main thing to watch out for is to install it as the `deploy_user` and **not** `root`.\\n\\nThe problem I had is that my specific deploy user didn\'t have permission to write to the location where rbenv installs its gems so if you are using rbenv or rvm then that is something to watch out for.\\n\\nI simply did\\n\\n    sudo gem install sass\\n\\nand that solved the problem.\\n\\nThe next thing was to follow the steps from the blog post to create the `.scss` files and also untracking the existing `screen.css` and deleting the local copy once we have everything we need in the sass stylesheets.\\n\\nThe problem we will have now is that git doesn\'t track empty directories so we will need to update the `deploy.rb` to create the `assets/css` directory when we deploy.\\n\\nTo build it locally if you are doing local development you can do the following from your theme root directory:\\n\\n    sass assets/sass/input.scss:assets/css/screen.css --style compressed\\n\\nYou can add the `--watch` option to continually monitor for changes.\\n\\nWe then need to update the `.gitignore` file so that `.css` and `.map` files can\'t accidentally be committed:\\n\\n    Capfile\\n    config/\\n    .sass-cache/\\n    *.css\\n    *.map\\n\\nThe last thing to do is then update the `execute` statements in `deploy.rb`\\n\\n    # symlink REVISION file\\n    execute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/REVISION /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/REVISION\'\\n      \\n     # create css directory for our compiled stylesheet to go in\\n    execute \'sudo mkdir /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/assets/css\'\\n      \\n    # symlink all the files from the current release to the theme root\\n    execute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/* /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\\n      \\n    # chown everything to be owned by our ghost user and not the deploy user\\n    execute \'sudo chown -R ghost_user:ghost_user /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\\n      \\n    # compile the css stylesheet from our sass files\\n    execute \'sudo sass /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/assets/sass/input.scss:/var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/assets/css/screen.css --style compressed\'\\n      \\n    # restart the forever process\\n    execute \'sudo forever restart /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/index.js\'\\n\\nDon\'t forget to push your changes to your git repo before deploying.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>This post is a follow-on from <a href=\"https://martincarlin.uk/2016/02/14/how-to-use-capistrano-3-for-ghost-theme-deployment/\">How to Use Capistrano 3 for Ghost Theme Deployment</a>, so please read that first.</p>\n<p>The aim of this post is to introduce SASS to the workflow instead of vanilla CSS.</p>\n<p>I followed this excellent blog post <a href=\"https://www.ghostforbeginners.com/using-sass-with-ghost/\">here</a> but I will describe what specific changes I made to my local project.</p>\n<p>First off, as the post points out, you need to install the SASS gem both to your local machine and your production server.</p>\n<pre><code>gem install sass\n</code></pre>\n<p>When installing on production, the main thing to watch out for is to install it as the <code>deploy_user</code> and <strong>not</strong> <code>root</code>.</p>\n<p>The problem I had is that my specific deploy user didn\'t have permission to write to the location where rbenv installs its gems so if you are using rbenv or rvm then that is something to watch out for.</p>\n<p>I simply did</p>\n<pre><code>sudo gem install sass\n</code></pre>\n<p>and that solved the problem.</p>\n<p>The next thing was to follow the steps from the blog post to create the <code>.scss</code> files and also untracking the existing <code>screen.css</code> and deleting the local copy once we have everything we need in the sass stylesheets.</p>\n<p>The problem we will have now is that git doesn\'t track empty directories so we will need to update the <code>deploy.rb</code> to create the <code>assets/css</code> directory when we deploy.</p>\n<p>To build it locally if you are doing local development you can do the following from your theme root directory:</p>\n<pre><code>sass assets/sass/input.scss:assets/css/screen.css --style compressed\n</code></pre>\n<p>You can add the <code>--watch</code> option to continually monitor for changes.</p>\n<p>We then need to update the <code>.gitignore</code> file so that <code>.css</code> and <code>.map</code> files can\'t accidentally be committed:</p>\n<pre><code>Capfile\nconfig/\n.sass-cache/\n*.css\n*.map\n</code></pre>\n<p>The last thing to do is then update the <code>execute</code> statements in <code>deploy.rb</code></p>\n<pre><code># symlink REVISION file\nexecute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/REVISION /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/REVISION\'\n  \n # create css directory for our compiled stylesheet to go in\nexecute \'sudo mkdir /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/assets/css\'\n  \n# symlink all the files from the current release to the theme root\nexecute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/* /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n  \n# chown everything to be owned by our ghost user and not the deploy user\nexecute \'sudo chown -R ghost_user:ghost_user /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n  \n# compile the css stylesheet from our sass files\nexecute \'sudo sass /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/assets/sass/input.scss:/var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/assets/css/screen.css --style compressed\'\n  \n# restart the forever process\nexecute \'sudo forever restart /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/index.js\'\n</code></pre>\n<p>Don\'t forget to push your changes to your git repo before deploying.</p>\n</div>','19','This post is a follow-on from How to Use Capistrano 3 for Ghost Theme Deployment\n[https://martincarlin.uk/2016/02/14/how-to-use-capistrano-3-for-ghost-theme-deployment/]\n, so please read that first.\n\nThe aim of this post is to introduce SASS to the workflow instead of vanilla\nCSS.\n\nI followed this excellent blog post here\n[https://www.ghostforbeginners.com/using-sass-with-ghost/]  but I will describe\nwhat specific changes I made to my local project.\n\nFirst off, as the post points out, you need to install the SASS gem both to your\nlocal machine and your production server.\n\ngem install sass\n\n\nWhen installing on production, the main thing to watch out for is to install it\nas the deploy_user  and not  root.\n\nThe problem I had is that my specific deploy user didn\'t have permission to\nwrite to the location where rbenv installs its gems so if you are using rbenv or\nrvm then that is something to watch out for.\n\nI simply did\n\nsudo gem install sass\n\n\nand that solved the problem.\n\nThe next thing was to follow the steps from the blog post to create the .scss \nfiles and also untracking the existing screen.css  and deleting the local copy\nonce we have everything we need in the sass stylesheets.\n\nThe problem we will have now is that git doesn\'t track empty directories so we\nwill need to update the deploy.rb  to create the assets/css  directory when we\ndeploy.\n\nTo build it locally if you are doing local development you can do the following\nfrom your theme root directory:\n\nsass assets/sass/input.scss:assets/css/screen.css --style compressed\n\n\nYou can add the --watch  option to continually monitor for changes.\n\nWe then need to update the .gitignore  file so that .css  and .map  files can\'t\naccidentally be committed:\n\nCapfile\nconfig/\n.sass-cache/\n*.css\n*.map\n\n\nThe last thing to do is then update the execute  statements in deploy.rb\n\n# symlink REVISION file\nexecute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/REVISION /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/REVISION\'\n  \n # create css directory for our compiled stylesheet to go in\nexecute \'sudo mkdir /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/assets/css\'\n  \n# symlink all the files from the current release to the theme root\nexecute \'sudo ln -sf /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/* /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n  \n# chown everything to be owned by our ghost user and not the deploy user\nexecute \'sudo chown -R ghost_user:ghost_user /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name\'\n  \n# compile the css stylesheet from our sass files\nexecute \'sudo sass /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/assets/sass/input.scss:/var/www/path_to_ghost_install/content/themes/theme_name/current/assets/css/screen.css --style compressed\'\n  \n# restart the forever process\nexecute \'sudo forever restart /var/www/path_to_ghost_install/index.js\'\n\n\nDon\'t forget to push your changes to your git repo before deploying.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-02-16 11:09:37','1','2016-02-16 11:29:23','1','2016-02-16 11:28:00','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb95','0ebb6b1a-df93-4888-8cf3-f4aa1abf9db5','Gulp','gulp','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"I recently spent a productive weekend eventually learning gulp and after reading countless blog posts and tutorials, I finally managed to get a workflow together that worked perfectly for me - spinning up a local web server, SASS compilation, asset minification and js uglifying, as well as (cached) image optimisation, and last but not least, deploying.\\n\\nIf I remember correctly, the vast majority of this came from one source but I cannot remember where, so apologies for that.\\n\\nThe changes I made included using `gulp-connect-php` and figuring out how to get it to point to the `app` directory and how to run the watching and SASS compilation tasks upon starting the server.\\n\\nAfter that, it just needed a teak to also compile the SASS before trying to minify the CSS.\\n\\nFinally, the last bit of pain was trying to figure out the deployment - it worked fine but everything was under the `dist` directory which I didn\'t want, the `rsyncConf.root = \'dist\';` sorts that issue out.\\n\\n<script src=\\\"https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/2abdad2efa48bb8b45bf.js\\\"></script>\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>I recently spent a productive weekend eventually learning gulp and after reading countless blog posts and tutorials, I finally managed to get a workflow together that worked perfectly for me - spinning up a local web server, SASS compilation, asset minification and js uglifying, as well as (cached) image optimisation, and last but not least, deploying.</p>\n<p>If I remember correctly, the vast majority of this came from one source but I cannot remember where, so apologies for that.</p>\n<p>The changes I made included using <code>gulp-connect-php</code> and figuring out how to get it to point to the <code>app</code> directory and how to run the watching and SASS compilation tasks upon starting the server.</p>\n<p>After that, it just needed a teak to also compile the SASS before trying to minify the CSS.</p>\n<p>Finally, the last bit of pain was trying to figure out the deployment - it worked fine but everything was under the <code>dist</code> directory which I didn\'t want, the <code>rsyncConf.root = \'dist\';</code> sorts that issue out.</p>\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/2abdad2efa48bb8b45bf.js\"></script></div>','20','I recently spent a productive weekend eventually learning gulp and after reading\ncountless blog posts and tutorials, I finally managed to get a workflow together\nthat worked perfectly for me - spinning up a local web server, SASS compilation,\nasset minification and js uglifying, as well as (cached) image optimisation, and\nlast but not least, deploying.\n\nIf I remember correctly, the vast majority of this came from one source but I\ncannot remember where, so apologies for that.\n\nThe changes I made included using gulp-connect-php  and figuring out how to get\nit to point to the app  directory and how to run the watching and SASS\ncompilation tasks upon starting the server.\n\nAfter that, it just needed a teak to also compile the SASS before trying to\nminify the CSS.\n\nFinally, the last bit of pain was trying to figure out the deployment - it\nworked fine but everything was under the dist  directory which I didn\'t want,\nthe rsyncConf.root = \'dist\';  sorts that issue out.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-03-16 14:05:21','1','2016-03-16 14:12:39','1','2016-03-16 14:09:19','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb98','2e30a5a7-0927-4803-86f3-374c58099b76','FAO Recruiters','fao-recruiters','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"Hello there! I am constantly updating this page and it\'s quite lengthy at the moment but please have a read and feel free to let me know what you think.\\n\\nAs you might imagine, I receive a fair amount of enquiries from recruiters and I find myself now saying the same things over and over, so I thought that putting something here that I can link to might be useful so that it doesn\'t take me as long to reply.\\n\\nI genuinely don\'t mind anyone getting in touch via email or LinkedIn as then I can reply whenever and wherever I like, but it seems to be the opposite with every person who gets in touch wanting *\'5 minutes\'* on the phone. The problem with that is that at least with emails and messages I can try and reply to everybody and treat them equally, with phone calls I can manage a couple before it becomes a chore and a distraction (i.e. from work), especially since I often have to find a quiet area to take the call away from my desk. (Cold) Calling from a withheld number doesn\'t really help either. \\n\\nAlso - don\'t chase me on my work phone by going through the directory tree, that\'s happened only a couple of times but you are off your rocker if you expect someone to talk openly about new roles when they could be sitting next to their boss.\\n\\nTaking calls also tends to be a complete waste of time as 95% of roles that I am contacted for are either not suitable, I have been contacted about the same one before from someone else, or just not of interest for one reason or another.\\n\\nTherefore, the way I like to approach it is to receive any roles you wish to send (with job spec) that you think I am suitable for and if they are something that I do want to go ahead with, that\'s when we can arrange a call to discuss. This helps to save us both time I\'m sure.\\n\\nIf you are contacting me, please send the following rather than being secretive and requiring a handful of messages to find out all the information I need (although I can understand and sympathise, but I can confirm that I am not a recruiter looking to steal your contacts):\\n\\n\\n- **- Name of the company**\\n- **- Salary range**\\n- **- Any benefits or perks**\\n- **- Location**\\n- **- Working hours**\\n- **- Technology stack - what\'s required and what can be learned**\\n- **- Culture**\\n- **- Dress code**\\n- **- Possibilities of working from home on occasion**\\n- **- Job spec**\\n\\nThe reason for requiring these is that there is no way I can make an informed decision about whether to proceed any further without knowing all of the above.\\n\\nTo cut to the chase and help narrow things down, I am not interested in working for an organisation caught up in red-tape that requires business dress to sit behind a desk and code.\\n\\nI currently work 9 - 5 at the moment so I\'m also not that keen if the role is 9 - 5.30 for example but it depends on the individual role, some I have been offered have meant a minuscule increase when you factor in those extra hours over the course of a year, so it definitely wasn\'t worth the move.\\n\\nI have had recruiters in the past take a condescending attitude about asking about trivial things such as working hours because the privilege of working for their client should be enough to disregard it but I think it\'s definitely important when you consider the above, what if I never bothered to ask and only found out when I received the contract?\\n\\nI also like to work on Macs so if it\'s Windows PCs that are used then again it\'s not of much interest, sorry - once you go Mac you don\'t go back.\\n\\nI am based outside of Glasgow (Motherwell) so roles in Edinburgh are also not particularly of interest. It would also be a bonus if the role was commutable by car (i.e. some form of parking provided or affordable near by) in order to avoid having to pay for public transport on top of my own.\\n\\nAlso, I have been using Ruby on Rails in my current role so if the role involves PHP then it\'s wise to point out that in any role I have used PHP, it\'s always been custom in-house \'frameworks\' that I have worked on, so even though I know PHP, I haven\'t had a chance to use any of the modern stuff professionally but I am using Laravel for a freelance project.\\n\\nPersonally, I don\'t think frameworks are an issue but it\'s whether that is deemed acceptable from the hiring company or not if it\'s an issue for them.\\n\\nThe only other thing to mention is that roles involving front and back-end work would be preferential as opposed to ones that are purely one or the other.\\n\\nI appreciate that all sounds extremely fussy but there is not much point in changing jobs if it\'s not better in almost every aspect from my point of view.\\n\\nI know that I have spoken to a lot of recruiters recently and I appreciate what you have sent and always attempted to be open and honest about any roles I\'ve been approached about, but nothing has caught my eye so far. A lot of the time it\'s hard to tell what the companies are like or what they actually do because their websites aren\'t very informative and the generic spiel about how good the client is doesn\'t really offer much either as every single company is innovative, exciting, etc.\\n\\nI also look up companies on Glassdoor, so if they have a lowscore on there then that sets of alarm bells, particularly if there have been one or more rounds of redundancies.\\n\\nOne thing that I have found annoying is recruiters getting in touch and then I reply with my thoughts and then I don\'t hear back (probably because of the fussiness, but I only want to make a move for the right job), until the next time I update my CV on Monster and then they conveniently forget about that time where they never got back to me.\\n\\nChances are, even if you come back with the perfect role then I won\'t be interested.\\n\\nThere has even been a case of me being interested in a role and not hearing back so I\'m not sure what the etiquette is there - apply direct?? (The role wasn\'t news to me since I had been contemplating applying directly for months but I was prepared to go through the recruiter when they got in touch about it.)\\n\\nI think that\'s everything, thanks for reading!\\n\\nCheers,\\nMartin\\n\\n\\n\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>Hello there! I am constantly updating this page and it\'s quite lengthy at the moment but please have a read and feel free to let me know what you think.</p>\n<p>As you might imagine, I receive a fair amount of enquiries from recruiters and I find myself now saying the same things over and over, so I thought that putting something here that I can link to might be useful so that it doesn\'t take me as long to reply.</p>\n<p>I genuinely don\'t mind anyone getting in touch via email or LinkedIn as then I can reply whenever and wherever I like, but it seems to be the opposite with every person who gets in touch wanting <em>\'5 minutes\'</em> on the phone. The problem with that is that at least with emails and messages I can try and reply to everybody and treat them equally, with phone calls I can manage a couple before it becomes a chore and a distraction (i.e. from work), especially since I often have to find a quiet area to take the call away from my desk. (Cold) Calling from a withheld number doesn\'t really help either.</p>\n<p>Also - don\'t chase me on my work phone by going through the directory tree, that\'s happened only a couple of times but you are off your rocker if you expect someone to talk openly about new roles when they could be sitting next to their boss.</p>\n<p>Taking calls also tends to be a complete waste of time as 95% of roles that I am contacted for are either not suitable, I have been contacted about the same one before from someone else, or just not of interest for one reason or another.</p>\n<p>Therefore, the way I like to approach it is to receive any roles you wish to send (with job spec) that you think I am suitable for and if they are something that I do want to go ahead with, that\'s when we can arrange a call to discuss. This helps to save us both time I\'m sure.</p>\n<p>If you are contacting me, please send the following rather than being secretive and requiring a handful of messages to find out all the information I need (although I can understand and sympathise, but I can confirm that I am not a recruiter looking to steal your contacts):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>- Name of the company</strong></li>\n<li><strong>- Salary range</strong></li>\n<li><strong>- Any benefits or perks</strong></li>\n<li><strong>- Location</strong></li>\n<li><strong>- Working hours</strong></li>\n<li><strong>- Technology stack - what\'s required and what can be learned</strong></li>\n<li><strong>- Culture</strong></li>\n<li><strong>- Dress code</strong></li>\n<li><strong>- Possibilities of working from home on occasion</strong></li>\n<li><strong>- Job spec</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The reason for requiring these is that there is no way I can make an informed decision about whether to proceed any further without knowing all of the above.</p>\n<p>To cut to the chase and help narrow things down, I am not interested in working for an organisation caught up in red-tape that requires business dress to sit behind a desk and code.</p>\n<p>I currently work 9 - 5 at the moment so I\'m also not that keen if the role is 9 - 5.30 for example but it depends on the individual role, some I have been offered have meant a minuscule increase when you factor in those extra hours over the course of a year, so it definitely wasn\'t worth the move.</p>\n<p>I have had recruiters in the past take a condescending attitude about asking about trivial things such as working hours because the privilege of working for their client should be enough to disregard it but I think it\'s definitely important when you consider the above, what if I never bothered to ask and only found out when I received the contract?</p>\n<p>I also like to work on Macs so if it\'s Windows PCs that are used then again it\'s not of much interest, sorry - once you go Mac you don\'t go back.</p>\n<p>I am based outside of Glasgow (Motherwell) so roles in Edinburgh are also not particularly of interest. It would also be a bonus if the role was commutable by car (i.e. some form of parking provided or affordable near by) in order to avoid having to pay for public transport on top of my own.</p>\n<p>Also, I have been using Ruby on Rails in my current role so if the role involves PHP then it\'s wise to point out that in any role I have used PHP, it\'s always been custom in-house \'frameworks\' that I have worked on, so even though I know PHP, I haven\'t had a chance to use any of the modern stuff professionally but I am using Laravel for a freelance project.</p>\n<p>Personally, I don\'t think frameworks are an issue but it\'s whether that is deemed acceptable from the hiring company or not if it\'s an issue for them.</p>\n<p>The only other thing to mention is that roles involving front and back-end work would be preferential as opposed to ones that are purely one or the other.</p>\n<p>I appreciate that all sounds extremely fussy but there is not much point in changing jobs if it\'s not better in almost every aspect from my point of view.</p>\n<p>I know that I have spoken to a lot of recruiters recently and I appreciate what you have sent and always attempted to be open and honest about any roles I\'ve been approached about, but nothing has caught my eye so far. A lot of the time it\'s hard to tell what the companies are like or what they actually do because their websites aren\'t very informative and the generic spiel about how good the client is doesn\'t really offer much either as every single company is innovative, exciting, etc.</p>\n<p>I also look up companies on Glassdoor, so if they have a lowscore on there then that sets of alarm bells, particularly if there have been one or more rounds of redundancies.</p>\n<p>One thing that I have found annoying is recruiters getting in touch and then I reply with my thoughts and then I don\'t hear back (probably because of the fussiness, but I only want to make a move for the right job), until the next time I update my CV on Monster and then they conveniently forget about that time where they never got back to me.</p>\n<p>Chances are, even if you come back with the perfect role then I won\'t be interested.</p>\n<p>There has even been a case of me being interested in a role and not hearing back so I\'m not sure what the etiquette is there - apply direct?? (The role wasn\'t news to me since I had been contemplating applying directly for months but I was prepared to go through the recruiter when they got in touch about it.)</p>\n<p>I think that\'s everything, thanks for reading!</p>\n<p>Cheers,<br>\nMartin</p>\n</div>','21','Hello there! I am constantly updating this page and it\'s quite lengthy at the\nmoment but please have a read and feel free to let me know what you think.\n\nAs you might imagine, I receive a fair amount of enquiries from recruiters and I\nfind myself now saying the same things over and over, so I thought that putting\nsomething here that I can link to might be useful so that it doesn\'t take me as\nlong to reply.\n\nI genuinely don\'t mind anyone getting in touch via email or LinkedIn as then I\ncan reply whenever and wherever I like, but it seems to be the opposite with\nevery person who gets in touch wanting \'5 minutes\'  on the phone. The problem\nwith that is that at least with emails and messages I can try and reply to\neverybody and treat them equally, with phone calls I can manage a couple before\nit becomes a chore and a distraction (i.e. from work), especially since I often\nhave to find a quiet area to take the call away from my desk. (Cold) Calling\nfrom a withheld number doesn\'t really help either.\n\nAlso - don\'t chase me on my work phone by going through the directory tree,\nthat\'s happened only a couple of times but you are off your rocker if you expect\nsomeone to talk openly about new roles when they could be sitting next to their\nboss.\n\nTaking calls also tends to be a complete waste of time as 95% of roles that I am\ncontacted for are either not suitable, I have been contacted about the same one\nbefore from someone else, or just not of interest for one reason or another.\n\nTherefore, the way I like to approach it is to receive any roles you wish to\nsend (with job spec) that you think I am suitable for and if they are something\nthat I do want to go ahead with, that\'s when we can arrange a call to discuss.\nThis helps to save us both time I\'m sure.\n\nIf you are contacting me, please send the following rather than being secretive\nand requiring a handful of messages to find out all the information I need\n(although I can understand and sympathise, but I can confirm that I am not a\nrecruiter looking to steal your contacts):\n\n * - Name of the company\n * - Salary range\n * - Any benefits or perks\n * - Location\n * - Working hours\n * - Technology stack - what\'s required and what can be learned\n * - Culture\n * - Dress code\n * - Possibilities of working from home on occasion\n * - Job spec\n\nThe reason for requiring these is that there is no way I can make an informed\ndecision about whether to proceed any further without knowing all of the above.\n\nTo cut to the chase and help narrow things down, I am not interested in working\nfor an organisation caught up in red-tape that requires business dress to sit\nbehind a desk and code.\n\nI currently work 9 - 5 at the moment so I\'m also not that keen if the role is 9\n- 5.30 for example but it depends on the individual role, some I have been\noffered have meant a minuscule increase when you factor in those extra hours\nover the course of a year, so it definitely wasn\'t worth the move.\n\nI have had recruiters in the past take a condescending attitude about asking\nabout trivial things such as working hours because the privilege of working for\ntheir client should be enough to disregard it but I think it\'s definitely\nimportant when you consider the above, what if I never bothered to ask and only\nfound out when I received the contract?\n\nI also like to work on Macs so if it\'s Windows PCs that are used then again it\'s\nnot of much interest, sorry - once you go Mac you don\'t go back.\n\nI am based outside of Glasgow (Motherwell) so roles in Edinburgh are also not\nparticularly of interest. It would also be a bonus if the role was commutable by\ncar (i.e. some form of parking provided or affordable near by) in order to avoid\nhaving to pay for public transport on top of my own.\n\nAlso, I have been using Ruby on Rails in my current role so if the role involves\nPHP then it\'s wise to point out that in any role I have used PHP, it\'s always\nbeen custom in-house \'frameworks\' that I have worked on, so even though I know\nPHP, I haven\'t had a chance to use any of the modern stuff professionally but I\nam using Laravel for a freelance project.\n\nPersonally, I don\'t think frameworks are an issue but it\'s whether that is\ndeemed acceptable from the hiring company or not if it\'s an issue for them.\n\nThe only other thing to mention is that roles involving front and back-end work\nwould be preferential as opposed to ones that are purely one or the other.\n\nI appreciate that all sounds extremely fussy but there is not much point in\nchanging jobs if it\'s not better in almost every aspect from my point of view.\n\nI know that I have spoken to a lot of recruiters recently and I appreciate what\nyou have sent and always attempted to be open and honest about any roles I\'ve\nbeen approached about, but nothing has caught my eye so far. A lot of the time\nit\'s hard to tell what the companies are like or what they actually do because\ntheir websites aren\'t very informative and the generic spiel about how good the\nclient is doesn\'t really offer much either as every single company is\ninnovative, exciting, etc.\n\nI also look up companies on Glassdoor, so if they have a lowscore on there then\nthat sets of alarm bells, particularly if there have been one or more rounds of\nredundancies.\n\nOne thing that I have found annoying is recruiters getting in touch and then I\nreply with my thoughts and then I don\'t hear back (probably because of the\nfussiness, but I only want to make a move for the right job), until the next\ntime I update my CV on Monster and then they conveniently forget about that time\nwhere they never got back to me.\n\nChances are, even if you come back with the perfect role then I won\'t be\ninterested.\n\nThere has even been a case of me being interested in a role and not hearing back\nso I\'m not sure what the etiquette is there - apply direct?? (The role wasn\'t\nnews to me since I had been contemplating applying directly for months but I was\nprepared to go through the recruiter when they got in touch about it.)\n\nI think that\'s everything, thanks for reading!\n\nCheers,\nMartin',NULL,0,1,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-06-14 09:42:00','1','2016-08-05 15:20:07','1','2016-06-14 10:41:06','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb99','d11b37d4-258a-44a9-9f91-8658083d9dad','Upgrade PHP from 5.4 to 5.6 on CentOS 7','upgrade-php-from-5-4-to-5-6-on-centos-7','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"I recently went through the trials and tribulations of upgrading PHP on my VM running CentOS 7 so I thought I\'d document how I did it.\\n\\nThe key to it is the [Remi RPM Repository](http://rpms.famillecollet.com/) but I made the dumb mistake of adding the repos for the CentOS 6 version of the 5.6 upgrade so to fix that I removed all of the repos I just added:\\n\\n    rm -rf /etc/yum.repos.d/remi*\\n\\nand then I just added what I needed manually:\\n\\n    cat > /etc/yum.repos.d/remi-php56.repo << EOF\\n    [remi-php56]\\n    name=remi-php56\\n    baseurl=http://rpms.famillecollet.com/enterprise/7/php56/x86_64/\\n    enabled=1\\n    gpgcheck=0\\n    EOF\\n\\nThen you need to clear the cache:\\n\\n    yum clean expire-cache\\n\\nand re-run the update\\n\\n    yum update\\n\\nYou might get some errors like so:\\n\\n    Error: Package: php-gd-5.6.22-1.el7.remi.x86_64 (remi-php56)\\n           Requires: libgd.so.3()(64bit)\\n    Error: Package: php-gd-5.6.22-1.el7.remi.x86_64 (remi-php56)\\n           Requires: gd-last(x86-64) >= 2.1.1\\n    Error: Package: php-pecl-zip-1.13.2-1.el7.remi.5.6.x86_64 (remi-php56)\\n           Requires: libzip.so.4()(64bit)\\n     You could try using --skip-broken to work around the problem\\n     You could try running: rpm -Va --nofiles --nodigest\\n\\nTo fix these:\\n\\n    wget http://rpms.famillecollet.com/enterprise/7/remi/x86_64/gd-last-2.2.1-2.el7.remi.x86_64.rpm\\n\\n    yum localinstall gd-last-*.rpm\\n\\n    wget http://rpms.famillecollet.com/enterprise/7/remi/x86_64/libzip-last-1.1.3-1.el7.remi.x86_64.rpm\\n\\n    yum localinstall libzip-last-*.rpm\\n\\n    yum update\\n\\nThat should have worked, so try running `php -v`.\\n\\nYou might have some warnings like I did:\\n\\n    PHP Warning:  PHP Startup: newrelic: Unable to initialize module\\n    Module compiled with module API=20100525\\n    PHP    compiled with module API=20131226\\n    These options need to match\\n    in Unknown on line 0\\n    PHP Warning:  PHP Startup: ssh2: Unable to initialize module\\n    Module compiled with module API=20100525\\n    PHP    compiled with module API=20131226\\n    These options need to match\\n    in Unknown on line 0\\n    PHP 5.6.22 (cli) (built: May 26 2016 15:36:45)\\n    Copyright (c) 1997-2016 The PHP Group\\n    Zend Engine v2.6.0, Copyright (c) 1998-2016 Zend Technologies\\n\\nNew Relic is easy to fix: \\n\\n    newrelic-install install\\n\\nand for ssh2, I just removed it:\\n\\n    rm -rf /etc/php.d/ssh2.ini\\n\\nre-reun `php -v` to confirm that the warnings are gone.\\n\\nHope it helps.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>I recently went through the trials and tribulations of upgrading PHP on my VM running CentOS 7 so I thought I\'d document how I did it.</p>\n<p>The key to it is the <a href=\"http://rpms.famillecollet.com/\">Remi RPM Repository</a> but I made the dumb mistake of adding the repos for the CentOS 6 version of the 5.6 upgrade so to fix that I removed all of the repos I just added:</p>\n<pre><code>rm -rf /etc/yum.repos.d/remi*\n</code></pre>\n<p>and then I just added what I needed manually:</p>\n<pre><code>cat &gt; /etc/yum.repos.d/remi-php56.repo &lt;&lt; EOF\n[remi-php56]\nname=remi-php56\nbaseurl=http://rpms.famillecollet.com/enterprise/7/php56/x86_64/\nenabled=1\ngpgcheck=0\nEOF\n</code></pre>\n<p>Then you need to clear the cache:</p>\n<pre><code>yum clean expire-cache\n</code></pre>\n<p>and re-run the update</p>\n<pre><code>yum update\n</code></pre>\n<p>You might get some errors like so:</p>\n<pre><code>Error: Package: php-gd-5.6.22-1.el7.remi.x86_64 (remi-php56)\n       Requires: libgd.so.3()(64bit)\nError: Package: php-gd-5.6.22-1.el7.remi.x86_64 (remi-php56)\n       Requires: gd-last(x86-64) &gt;= 2.1.1\nError: Package: php-pecl-zip-1.13.2-1.el7.remi.5.6.x86_64 (remi-php56)\n       Requires: libzip.so.4()(64bit)\n You could try using --skip-broken to work around the problem\n You could try running: rpm -Va --nofiles --nodigest\n</code></pre>\n<p>To fix these:</p>\n<pre><code>wget http://rpms.famillecollet.com/enterprise/7/remi/x86_64/gd-last-2.2.1-2.el7.remi.x86_64.rpm\n\nyum localinstall gd-last-*.rpm\n\nwget http://rpms.famillecollet.com/enterprise/7/remi/x86_64/libzip-last-1.1.3-1.el7.remi.x86_64.rpm\n\nyum localinstall libzip-last-*.rpm\n\nyum update\n</code></pre>\n<p>That should have worked, so try running <code>php -v</code>.</p>\n<p>You might have some warnings like I did:</p>\n<pre><code>PHP Warning:  PHP Startup: newrelic: Unable to initialize module\nModule compiled with module API=20100525\nPHP    compiled with module API=20131226\nThese options need to match\nin Unknown on line 0\nPHP Warning:  PHP Startup: ssh2: Unable to initialize module\nModule compiled with module API=20100525\nPHP    compiled with module API=20131226\nThese options need to match\nin Unknown on line 0\nPHP 5.6.22 (cli) (built: May 26 2016 15:36:45)\nCopyright (c) 1997-2016 The PHP Group\nZend Engine v2.6.0, Copyright (c) 1998-2016 Zend Technologies\n</code></pre>\n<p>New Relic is easy to fix:</p>\n<pre><code>newrelic-install install\n</code></pre>\n<p>and for ssh2, I just removed it:</p>\n<pre><code>rm -rf /etc/php.d/ssh2.ini\n</code></pre>\n<p>re-reun <code>php -v</code> to confirm that the warnings are gone.</p>\n<p>Hope it helps.</p>\n</div>','22','I recently went through the trials and tribulations of upgrading PHP on my VM\nrunning CentOS 7 so I thought I\'d document how I did it.\n\nThe key to it is the Remi RPM Repository [http://rpms.famillecollet.com/]  but I\nmade the dumb mistake of adding the repos for the CentOS 6 version of the 5.6\nupgrade so to fix that I removed all of the repos I just added:\n\nrm -rf /etc/yum.repos.d/remi*\n\n\nand then I just added what I needed manually:\n\ncat > /etc/yum.repos.d/remi-php56.repo << EOF\n[remi-php56]\nname=remi-php56\nbaseurl=http://rpms.famillecollet.com/enterprise/7/php56/x86_64/\nenabled=1\ngpgcheck=0\nEOF\n\n\nThen you need to clear the cache:\n\nyum clean expire-cache\n\n\nand re-run the update\n\nyum update\n\n\nYou might get some errors like so:\n\nError: Package: php-gd-5.6.22-1.el7.remi.x86_64 (remi-php56)\n       Requires: libgd.so.3()(64bit)\nError: Package: php-gd-5.6.22-1.el7.remi.x86_64 (remi-php56)\n       Requires: gd-last(x86-64) >= 2.1.1\nError: Package: php-pecl-zip-1.13.2-1.el7.remi.5.6.x86_64 (remi-php56)\n       Requires: libzip.so.4()(64bit)\n You could try using --skip-broken to work around the problem\n You could try running: rpm -Va --nofiles --nodigest\n\n\nTo fix these:\n\nwget http://rpms.famillecollet.com/enterprise/7/remi/x86_64/gd-last-2.2.1-2.el7.remi.x86_64.rpm\n\nyum localinstall gd-last-*.rpm\n\nwget http://rpms.famillecollet.com/enterprise/7/remi/x86_64/libzip-last-1.1.3-1.el7.remi.x86_64.rpm\n\nyum localinstall libzip-last-*.rpm\n\nyum update\n\n\nThat should have worked, so try running php -v.\n\nYou might have some warnings like I did:\n\nPHP Warning:  PHP Startup: newrelic: Unable to initialize module\nModule compiled with module API=20100525\nPHP    compiled with module API=20131226\nThese options need to match\nin Unknown on line 0\nPHP Warning:  PHP Startup: ssh2: Unable to initialize module\nModule compiled with module API=20100525\nPHP    compiled with module API=20131226\nThese options need to match\nin Unknown on line 0\nPHP 5.6.22 (cli) (built: May 26 2016 15:36:45)\nCopyright (c) 1997-2016 The PHP Group\nZend Engine v2.6.0, Copyright (c) 1998-2016 Zend Technologies\n\n\nNew Relic is easy to fix:\n\nnewrelic-install install\n\n\nand for ssh2, I just removed it:\n\nrm -rf /etc/php.d/ssh2.ini\n\n\nre-reun php -v  to confirm that the warnings are gone.\n\nHope it helps.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-06-29 14:29:30','1','2016-06-29 14:37:55','1','2016-06-29 14:37:55','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2b9c47ff40bdeecb9d','7e035aff-f95b-4085-99da-e39157ff1bed','Tools, Software and Uses','tools-and-dev-environments','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"This is just a post to keep track of things I use.\\n\\nThanks to [wesbos](http://wesbos.com/), I use the Cobalt2 themes for [Sublime Text](https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Theme%20-%20Cobalt2) as well as [iTerm](https://github.com/wesbos/Cobalt2-iterm).\\n\\nThere is also a Cobalt2 theme for [SequelPro](https://github.com/atuttle/cobalt2-sequelpro) made by [Adam Tuttle](https://github.com/atuttle).\\n\\n<hr>\\n\\nThe pieces of software I use daily are:\\n\\n* [Sublime Text](https://www.sublimetext.com/)  \\n* [Sequel Pro](http://www.sequelpro.com/)  \\n* [iTerm](https://www.iterm2.com/)  \\n* [Transmit](https://panic.com/transmit/)\\n* [GitKraken](https://www.gitkraken.com/) (previously used [Tower](https://www.git-tower.com/))\\n* [Shuttle](http://fitztrev.github.io/shuttle/)\\n\\nand less often:\\n\\n* [Slack](https://slack.com/) (in [Franz](http://meetfranz.com/))\\n* [Polymail](https://polymail.io/)\\n* [CleanMyMac](http://macpaw.com/cleanmymac)\\n* [Duet](http://www.duetdisplay.com/)\\n* [TeamViewer](https://www.teamviewer.com/en/)\\n\\nSublime Text extensions\\n\\n* [GitGutter](https://github.com/jisaacks/GitGutter)\\n\\nMiscellaneous\\n\\n[Apple TV Screensavers](https://github.com/JohnCoates/Aerial)\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>This is just a post to keep track of things I use.</p>\n<p>Thanks to <a href=\"http://wesbos.com/\">wesbos</a>, I use the Cobalt2 themes for <a href=\"https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Theme%20-%20Cobalt2\">Sublime Text</a> as well as <a href=\"https://github.com/wesbos/Cobalt2-iterm\">iTerm</a>.</p>\n<p>There is also a Cobalt2 theme for <a href=\"https://github.com/atuttle/cobalt2-sequelpro\">SequelPro</a> made by <a href=\"https://github.com/atuttle\">Adam Tuttle</a>.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>The pieces of software I use daily are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.sublimetext.com/\">Sublime Text</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.sequelpro.com/\">Sequel Pro</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.iterm2.com/\">iTerm</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://panic.com/transmit/\">Transmit</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.gitkraken.com/\">GitKraken</a> (previously used <a href=\"https://www.git-tower.com/\">Tower</a>)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://fitztrev.github.io/shuttle/\">Shuttle</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>and less often:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://slack.com/\">Slack</a> (in <a href=\"http://meetfranz.com/\">Franz</a>)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://polymail.io/\">Polymail</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://macpaw.com/cleanmymac\">CleanMyMac</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.duetdisplay.com/\">Duet</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.teamviewer.com/en/\">TeamViewer</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Sublime Text extensions</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://github.com/jisaacks/GitGutter\">GitGutter</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Miscellaneous</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/JohnCoates/Aerial\">Apple TV Screensavers</a></p>\n</div>','23','This is just a post to keep track of things I use.\n\nThanks to wesbos [http://wesbos.com/], I use the Cobalt2 themes for Sublime Text\n[https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Theme%20-%20Cobalt2]  as well as iTerm\n[https://github.com/wesbos/Cobalt2-iterm].\n\nThere is also a Cobalt2 theme for SequelPro\n[https://github.com/atuttle/cobalt2-sequelpro]  made by Adam Tuttle\n[https://github.com/atuttle].\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nThe pieces of software I use daily are:\n\n * Sublime Text [https://www.sublimetext.com/]\n * Sequel Pro [http://www.sequelpro.com/]\n * iTerm [https://www.iterm2.com/]\n * Transmit [https://panic.com/transmit/]\n * GitKraken [https://www.gitkraken.com/]  (previously used Tower\n   [https://www.git-tower.com/])\n * Shuttle [http://fitztrev.github.io/shuttle/]\n\nand less often:\n\n * Slack [https://slack.com/]  (in Franz [http://meetfranz.com/])\n * Polymail [https://polymail.io/]\n * CleanMyMac [http://macpaw.com/cleanmymac]\n * Duet [http://www.duetdisplay.com/]\n * TeamViewer [https://www.teamviewer.com/en/]\n\nSublime Text extensions\n\n * GitGutter [https://github.com/jisaacks/GitGutter]\n\nMiscellaneous\n\nApple TV Screensavers [https://github.com/JohnCoates/Aerial]',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-07-22 13:40:20','1','2017-03-08 11:29:33','1','2016-07-22 13:53:57','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecb9f','dd0d3db9-0f6a-4166-bbfd-8750c39b6ce5','Git','git','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"These are my personal notes about git which might help others, most are self explanatory.\\n\\n#### **General**\\nTo create a new git repo in the current directory:  \\n[`git init`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-init)\\n\\nCheck the status of the repository, helpful for seeing what has changed:  \\n[`git status`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-status)\\n\\nSee last five commits: \\n[`git log`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-log)\\n\\nAdd a new file to the repo:  \\n[`git add <filename>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-add)\\n\\nShow changes to a file between commits:  \\n[`git diff <filename>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-diff)\\n\\nCommit changes to staging area:  \\n[`git commit -m <message>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-commit)\\n\\nSee latest commit:  \\n[`git show HEAD`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-show)\\n\\nDiscard changes to file in working directory:  \\n[`git checkout HEAD <filename>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-checkout)\\n\\nUnstage changes to file in working directory:  \\n[`git reset HEAD <filename>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-reset)\\n\\nRevert to previous commit identified by the SHA:  \\n[`git reset <sha>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-reset)\\n\\nList local branches:  \\n[`git branch`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-branch)\\n\\nCreate local copy of remote repo:  \\n[`git clone <remote repo url>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-clone)\\n\\nList remote repos:  \\n[`git remote -v`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-remote)\\n\\nPull changes from remote repo into local copy:  \\n[`git fetch`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-fetch)\\n\\nMerge remote origin into local branch:  \\n[`git merge origin/master`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-merge)\\n\\nPush branch to remote origin:  \\n[`git push origin <branch name>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-push)\\n\\nList modified files:\\n[`git diff --name-only`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-diff)\\n\\n<hr>\\n\\n#### **Everyday Workflow for Branching**\\n\\nCreate a new branch:  \\n[`git branch <new branch name>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-branch)\\n\\nCheckout the new branch:  \\n[`git checkout <new branch name>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-checkout)\\n\\nCommit changes to the new branch:  \\n[`git commit -a -m <message>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-commit)\\n\\nSwitch back to master:  \\n[`git checkout master`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-checkout)\\n\\nMerge branch to master:  \\n[`git merge <new branch name> master`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-merge)\\n\\nDelete branch:  \\n[`git branch -d <new branch name>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-branch)\\n\\nPush changes to origin:\\n[`git push origin`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-push)\\n\\n<hr>\\n\\n#### **Tagging** _(optional)_\\n\\nAdd a tag to the branch:  \\n[`git tag -a <tag name> -m \\\"message\\\"`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-tag)\\n\\nPush tag to remote repo: \\n[`git push origin <tag name>`](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-push)\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>These are my personal notes about git which might help others, most are self explanatory.</p>\n<h4 id=\"general\"><strong>General</strong></h4>\n<p>To create a new git repo in the current directory:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-init\"><code>git init</code></a></p>\n<p>Check the status of the repository, helpful for seeing what has changed:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-status\"><code>git status</code></a></p>\n<p>See last five commits:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-log\"><code>git log</code></a></p>\n<p>Add a new file to the repo:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-add\"><code>git add &lt;filename&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>Show changes to a file between commits:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-diff\"><code>git diff &lt;filename&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>Commit changes to staging area:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-commit\"><code>git commit -m &lt;message&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>See latest commit:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-show\"><code>git show HEAD</code></a></p>\n<p>Discard changes to file in working directory:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-checkout\"><code>git checkout HEAD &lt;filename&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>Unstage changes to file in working directory:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-reset\"><code>git reset HEAD &lt;filename&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>Revert to previous commit identified by the SHA:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-reset\"><code>git reset &lt;sha&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>List local branches:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-branch\"><code>git branch</code></a></p>\n<p>Create local copy of remote repo:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-clone\"><code>git clone &lt;remote repo url&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>List remote repos:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-remote\"><code>git remote -v</code></a></p>\n<p>Pull changes from remote repo into local copy:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-fetch\"><code>git fetch</code></a></p>\n<p>Merge remote origin into local branch:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-merge\"><code>git merge origin/master</code></a></p>\n<p>Push branch to remote origin:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-push\"><code>git push origin &lt;branch name&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>List modified files:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-diff\"><code>git diff --name-only</code></a></p>\n<hr>\n<h4 id=\"everydayworkflowforbranching\"><strong>Everyday Workflow for Branching</strong></h4>\n<p>Create a new branch:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-branch\"><code>git branch &lt;new branch name&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>Checkout the new branch:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-checkout\"><code>git checkout &lt;new branch name&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>Commit changes to the new branch:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-commit\"><code>git commit -a -m &lt;message&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>Switch back to master:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-checkout\"><code>git checkout master</code></a></p>\n<p>Merge branch to master:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-merge\"><code>git merge &lt;new branch name&gt; master</code></a></p>\n<p>Delete branch:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-branch\"><code>git branch -d &lt;new branch name&gt;</code></a></p>\n<p>Push changes to origin:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-push\"><code>git push origin</code></a></p>\n<hr>\n<h4 id=\"taggingoptional\"><strong>Tagging</strong> <em>(optional)</em></h4>\n<p>Add a tag to the branch:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-tag\"><code>git tag -a &lt;tag name&gt; -m &quot;message&quot;</code></a></p>\n<p>Push tag to remote repo:<br>\n<a href=\"https://git-scm.com/docs/git-push\"><code>git push origin &lt;tag name&gt;</code></a></p>\n</div>','24','These are my personal notes about git which might help others, most are self\nexplanatory.\n\nGeneral\nTo create a new git repo in the current directory:\ngit init [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-init]\n\nCheck the status of the repository, helpful for seeing what has changed:\ngit status [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-status]\n\nSee last five commits:\ngit log [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-log]\n\nAdd a new file to the repo:\ngit add <filename> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-add]\n\nShow changes to a file between commits:\ngit diff <filename> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-diff]\n\nCommit changes to staging area:\ngit commit -m <message> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-commit]\n\nSee latest commit:\ngit show HEAD [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-show]\n\nDiscard changes to file in working directory:\ngit checkout HEAD <filename> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-checkout]\n\nUnstage changes to file in working directory:\ngit reset HEAD <filename> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-reset]\n\nRevert to previous commit identified by the SHA:\ngit reset <sha> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-reset]\n\nList local branches:\ngit branch [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-branch]\n\nCreate local copy of remote repo:\ngit clone <remote repo url> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-clone]\n\nList remote repos:\ngit remote -v [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-remote]\n\nPull changes from remote repo into local copy:\ngit fetch [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-fetch]\n\nMerge remote origin into local branch:\ngit merge origin/master [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-merge]\n\nPush branch to remote origin:\ngit push origin <branch name> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-push]\n\nList modified files:\ngit diff --name-only [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-diff]\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nEveryday Workflow for Branching\nCreate a new branch:\ngit branch <new branch name> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-branch]\n\nCheckout the new branch:\ngit checkout <new branch name> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-checkout]\n\nCommit changes to the new branch:\ngit commit -a -m <message> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-commit]\n\nSwitch back to master:\ngit checkout master [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-checkout]\n\nMerge branch to master:\ngit merge <new branch name> master [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-merge]\n\nDelete branch:\ngit branch -d <new branch name> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-branch]\n\nPush changes to origin:\ngit push origin [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-push]\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nTagging  (optional)\nAdd a tag to the branch:\ngit tag -a <tag name> -m \"message\" [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-tag]\n\nPush tag to remote repo:\ngit push origin <tag name> [https://git-scm.com/docs/git-push]',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-07-22 14:04:38','1','2016-07-22 14:33:57','1','2016-07-22 14:32:17','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecba1','c23cc58e-42b0-443f-bb9d-74c59978abb9','Markdown Tips','markdown-tips','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"Markdown us usually pretty straightforward but I was struggling to think of a way to use a link in code blocks but thanks to this [answer](http://stackoverflow.com/a/28615106/634120) on StackOverflow you can do this:\\n\\n    [`this is code`](https://this_is_url/)\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>Markdown us usually pretty straightforward but I was struggling to think of a way to use a link in code blocks but thanks to this <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/a/28615106/634120\">answer</a> on StackOverflow you can do this:</p>\n<pre><code>[`this is code`](https://this_is_url/)</code></pre>\n</div>','25','Markdown us usually pretty straightforward but I was struggling to think of a\nway to use a link in code blocks but thanks to this answer\n[http://stackoverflow.com/a/28615106/634120]  on StackOverflow you can do this:\n\n[`this is code`](https://this_is_url/)',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-07-22 14:15:51','1','2016-07-22 14:17:07','1','2016-07-22 14:17:07','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecba2','c8897d2f-321b-43a9-9e2a-fb33e214f1dd','Rails Tips','rails-tips','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"### Use helper functions in models and controllers\\n\\nSometimes you just need to use ActionView functions in your models or controllers.\\n\\nA way to achieve this is to include them like so:\\n\\n    include ActionView::Helpers::TextHelper\\n\\nbut a nicer approach seems to be to use the function directly like so:\\n\\n    ActionController::Base.helpers.[FUNCTION_NAME] (arguments)\\n\\n### Better pagination - avoid multiple queries\\n\\nFirst, do your query as normal but with one difference.\\n\\n    results = ModelName.select(\'SQL_CALC_FOUND_ROWS model.*\')\\n\\n\\nand then immediately after, run the following:\\n\\n    total = ModelName.connection.execute(\'SELECT FOUND_ROWS()\')\\n\\nTo get the actual total number, you can use `.first` on the `total` object.\\n\\nThis works even when using limit and offset in the original query.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><h3 id=\"usehelperfunctionsinmodelsandcontrollers\">Use helper functions in models and controllers</h3>\n<p>Sometimes you just need to use ActionView functions in your models or controllers.</p>\n<p>A way to achieve this is to include them like so:</p>\n<pre><code>include ActionView::Helpers::TextHelper\n</code></pre>\n<p>but a nicer approach seems to be to use the function directly like so:</p>\n<pre><code>ActionController::Base.helpers.[FUNCTION_NAME] (arguments)\n</code></pre>\n<h3 id=\"betterpaginationavoidmultiplequeries\">Better pagination - avoid multiple queries</h3>\n<p>First, do your query as normal but with one difference.</p>\n<pre><code>results = ModelName.select(\'SQL_CALC_FOUND_ROWS model.*\')\n</code></pre>\n<p>and then immediately after, run the following:</p>\n<pre><code>total = ModelName.connection.execute(\'SELECT FOUND_ROWS()\')\n</code></pre>\n<p>To get the actual total number, you can use <code>.first</code> on the <code>total</code> object.</p>\n<p>This works even when using limit and offset in the original query.</p>\n</div>','26','Use helper functions in models and controllers\nSometimes you just need to use ActionView functions in your models or\ncontrollers.\n\nA way to achieve this is to include them like so:\n\ninclude ActionView::Helpers::TextHelper\n\n\nbut a nicer approach seems to be to use the function directly like so:\n\nActionController::Base.helpers.[FUNCTION_NAME] (arguments)\n\n\nBetter pagination - avoid multiple queries\nFirst, do your query as normal but with one difference.\n\nresults = ModelName.select(\'SQL_CALC_FOUND_ROWS model.*\')\n\n\nand then immediately after, run the following:\n\ntotal = ModelName.connection.execute(\'SELECT FOUND_ROWS()\')\n\n\nTo get the actual total number, you can use .first  on the total  object.\n\nThis works even when using limit and offset in the original query.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-07-26 11:02:56','1','2016-07-26 13:47:54','1','2016-07-26 11:04:25','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecba5','dd923819-5f68-4ea7-be6f-10bb5acec477','Using Deployer to Deploy a Laravel 5 Project','using-deployer-to-deploy-a-laravel-5-project','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"\\n## Update\\n\\nAfter writing the first version of the post, I wanted to go back to have another look at it as I wasn\'t quite happy.\\n\\nI was running `php vendor/bin/dep` for deploys since I installed Deployer as a local package.\\n\\nI changed that by installing globally `composer global require deployer/deployer`.\\n\\nThen I could use `dep` instead of `php vendor/bin/dep`.\\n\\nI then removed all of the tasks that were already defined in the Deployer Laravel recipe from my script to avoid cluttering. I didn\'t even notice that include before so I\'m glad I went back to have another look at this.\\n\\nAfter that I setup some variables at the top to avoid any confusion over what needed updating for individual use cases.\\n\\nI also followed the Laravel recipe and included the `.env` in the `shared_files` array.\\n\\nThe biggest change after that was to simply upload the `public/build` directory and its contents over having to do `npm install` and then `gulp --production`. \\n\\nThis makes the deploy **significantly** quicker and it also saves you having to install node and npm on production, as well as not having a `node_modules` directory for every release which would take up a significant amount of room.\\n\\nI was still having issues with the `bootstrap/cache` folder after my re-shuffle, so I removed that line from the top level `.gitignore` (can\'t remember if it was me that added that or not, but looking at [Laravel\'s .gitignore](https://github.com/laravel/laravel/blob/master/.gitignore) it must have been me) and that helped and saved needing a further task in the deploy. There is already a `.gitignore` in the `bootstrap/cache` directory so that nothing in there will be version controlled, but just having the empty directory saved endless amounts of pain.\\n\\nThe final piece of the puzzle was to run `chmod g+s <directory>` to make files inherit group to make files inherit the group from the parent directory (my parent directory had `martin:nginx` as the owner and group). Without that, all the newly deployed files were `martin:martin` which didn\'t work for my configuration since nginx is running as .... `nginx`.\\n\\nNew gist:\\n<script src=\\\"https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/be641908dba85bfa39c642501d0cdfb8.js\\\"></script>\\n\\n---\\n\\n\\nI recently tried using [Deployer](https://deployer.org/) for the first time to setup a deployment process for a Laravel 5 project, rather than using something like Capistrano that would require installing ruby and gems rather than just adding a Composer package.\\n\\nThis gist represents hours of heartbreaking errors trying to figure out why things weren\'t working, the main one being the first task:\\n\\n```\\n/**\\n * Create cache folder in bootstrap directory\\n */\\ntask(\'deploy:cache_folder\', function() {\\n  run(\'mkdir {{release_path}}/bootstrap/cache\');\\n})->desc(\'Manually create cache folder\');\\n```\\n\\nI was getting an error saying that `bootstrap/cache/services.php` didn\'t exist when trying to run `php artisan optimize`. The solution seems to be creating the `bootstrap/cache` directory but of all the tutorials and blog posts I read, none mentioned it so I\'m not sure if this is a recent change since the `.gitignore` file has `/bootstrap/cache` in it but a 5.1 project I have doesn\'t.\\n\\nI think the rest is fairly self-explanatory, just replace the placeholders in the square brackets, the curly brackets are actually used by Deployer so don\'t change those!\\n\\nThis example is made a bit more complicated due to using elixir for assets, so that\'s why we have to have a task that runs `npm install`.\\n\\nI also wasn\'t sure what to do with the `.env` file since it\'s not in source control and obviously your local one will be based on a local environment, not production, so I decided just to create a `.env.production` file that gets uploaded and renamed to `.env`. The only problem I can see there is that if you are part of a team then you\'d need to communicate any changes somehow since it\'s not meant to be version controlled.\\n\\n\\n<script src=\\\"https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/4e223248721e2d26a2b2aa6ffe452666.js\\\"></script>\\n\\nTo deploy, run `dep deploy`.\\n\\nIf you have any suggested improvements then I\'d love to hear them.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><h2 id=\"update\">Update</h2>\n<p>After writing the first version of the post, I wanted to go back to have another look at it as I wasn\'t quite happy.</p>\n<p>I was running <code>php vendor/bin/dep</code> for deploys since I installed Deployer as a local package.</p>\n<p>I changed that by installing globally <code>composer global require deployer/deployer</code>.</p>\n<p>Then I could use <code>dep</code> instead of <code>php vendor/bin/dep</code>.</p>\n<p>I then removed all of the tasks that were already defined in the Deployer Laravel recipe from my script to avoid cluttering. I didn\'t even notice that include before so I\'m glad I went back to have another look at this.</p>\n<p>After that I setup some variables at the top to avoid any confusion over what needed updating for individual use cases.</p>\n<p>I also followed the Laravel recipe and included the <code>.env</code> in the <code>shared_files</code> array.</p>\n<p>The biggest change after that was to simply upload the <code>public/build</code> directory and its contents over having to do <code>npm install</code> and then <code>gulp --production</code>.</p>\n<p>This makes the deploy <strong>significantly</strong> quicker and it also saves you having to install node and npm on production, as well as not having a <code>node_modules</code> directory for every release which would take up a significant amount of room.</p>\n<p>I was still having issues with the <code>bootstrap/cache</code> folder after my re-shuffle, so I removed that line from the top level <code>.gitignore</code> (can\'t remember if it was me that added that or not, but looking at <a href=\"https://github.com/laravel/laravel/blob/master/.gitignore\">Laravel\'s .gitignore</a> it must have been me) and that helped and saved needing a further task in the deploy. There is already a <code>.gitignore</code> in the <code>bootstrap/cache</code> directory so that nothing in there will be version controlled, but just having the empty directory saved endless amounts of pain.</p>\n<p>The final piece of the puzzle was to run <code>chmod g+s &lt;directory&gt;</code> to make files inherit group to make files inherit the group from the parent directory (my parent directory had <code>martin:nginx</code> as the owner and group). Without that, all the newly deployed files were <code>martin:martin</code> which didn\'t work for my configuration since nginx is running as .... <code>nginx</code>.</p>\n<p>New gist:</p>\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/be641908dba85bfa39c642501d0cdfb8.js\"></script>\n<hr>\n<p>I recently tried using <a href=\"https://deployer.org/\">Deployer</a> for the first time to setup a deployment process for a Laravel 5 project, rather than using something like Capistrano that would require installing ruby and gems rather than just adding a Composer package.</p>\n<p>This gist represents hours of heartbreaking errors trying to figure out why things weren\'t working, the main one being the first task:</p>\n<pre><code>/**\n * Create cache folder in bootstrap directory\n */\ntask(\'deploy:cache_folder\', function() {\n  run(\'mkdir {{release_path}}/bootstrap/cache\');\n})-&gt;desc(\'Manually create cache folder\');\n</code></pre>\n<p>I was getting an error saying that <code>bootstrap/cache/services.php</code> didn\'t exist when trying to run <code>php artisan optimize</code>. The solution seems to be creating the <code>bootstrap/cache</code> directory but of all the tutorials and blog posts I read, none mentioned it so I\'m not sure if this is a recent change since the <code>.gitignore</code> file has <code>/bootstrap/cache</code> in it but a 5.1 project I have doesn\'t.</p>\n<p>I think the rest is fairly self-explanatory, just replace the placeholders in the square brackets, the curly brackets are actually used by Deployer so don\'t change those!</p>\n<p>This example is made a bit more complicated due to using elixir for assets, so that\'s why we have to have a task that runs <code>npm install</code>.</p>\n<p>I also wasn\'t sure what to do with the <code>.env</code> file since it\'s not in source control and obviously your local one will be based on a local environment, not production, so I decided just to create a <code>.env.production</code> file that gets uploaded and renamed to <code>.env</code>. The only problem I can see there is that if you are part of a team then you\'d need to communicate any changes somehow since it\'s not meant to be version controlled.</p>\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/4e223248721e2d26a2b2aa6ffe452666.js\"></script>\n<p>To deploy, run <code>dep deploy</code>.</p>\n<p>If you have any suggested improvements then I\'d love to hear them.</p>\n</div>','27','Update\nAfter writing the first version of the post, I wanted to go back to have another\nlook at it as I wasn\'t quite happy.\n\nI was running php vendor/bin/dep  for deploys since I installed Deployer as a\nlocal package.\n\nI changed that by installing globally composer global require deployer/deployer.\n\nThen I could use dep  instead of php vendor/bin/dep.\n\nI then removed all of the tasks that were already defined in the Deployer\nLaravel recipe from my script to avoid cluttering. I didn\'t even notice that\ninclude before so I\'m glad I went back to have another look at this.\n\nAfter that I setup some variables at the top to avoid any confusion over what\nneeded updating for individual use cases.\n\nI also followed the Laravel recipe and included the .env  in the shared_files \narray.\n\nThe biggest change after that was to simply upload the public/build  directory\nand its contents over having to do npm install  and then gulp --production.\n\nThis makes the deploy significantly  quicker and it also saves you having to\ninstall node and npm on production, as well as not having a node_modules \ndirectory for every release which would take up a significant amount of room.\n\nI was still having issues with the bootstrap/cache  folder after my re-shuffle,\nso I removed that line from the top level .gitignore  (can\'t remember if it was\nme that added that or not, but looking at Laravel\'s .gitignore\n[https://github.com/laravel/laravel/blob/master/.gitignore]  it must have been\nme) and that helped and saved needing a further task in the deploy. There is\nalready a .gitignore  in the bootstrap/cache  directory so that nothing in there\nwill be version controlled, but just having the empty directory saved endless\namounts of pain.\n\nThe final piece of the puzzle was to run chmod g+s <directory>  to make files\ninherit group to make files inherit the group from the parent directory (my\nparent directory had martin:nginx  as the owner and group). Without that, all\nthe newly deployed files were martin:martin  which didn\'t work for my\nconfiguration since nginx is running as .... nginx.\n\nNew gist:\n\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nI recently tried using Deployer [https://deployer.org/]  for the first time to\nsetup a deployment process for a Laravel 5 project, rather than using something\nlike Capistrano that would require installing ruby and gems rather than just\nadding a Composer package.\n\nThis gist represents hours of heartbreaking errors trying to figure out why\nthings weren\'t working, the main one being the first task:\n\n/**\n * Create cache folder in bootstrap directory\n */\ntask(\'deploy:cache_folder\', function() {\n  run(\'mkdir {{release_path}}/bootstrap/cache\');\n})->desc(\'Manually create cache folder\');\n\n\nI was getting an error saying that bootstrap/cache/services.php  didn\'t exist\nwhen trying to run php artisan optimize. The solution seems to be creating the \nbootstrap/cache  directory but of all the tutorials and blog posts I read, none\nmentioned it so I\'m not sure if this is a recent change since the .gitignore \nfile has /bootstrap/cache  in it but a 5.1 project I have doesn\'t.\n\nI think the rest is fairly self-explanatory, just replace the placeholders in\nthe square brackets, the curly brackets are actually used by Deployer so don\'t\nchange those!\n\nThis example is made a bit more complicated due to using elixir for assets, so\nthat\'s why we have to have a task that runs npm install.\n\nI also wasn\'t sure what to do with the .env  file since it\'s not in source\ncontrol and obviously your local one will be based on a local environment, not\nproduction, so I decided just to create a .env.production  file that gets\nuploaded and renamed to .env. The only problem I can see there is that if you\nare part of a team then you\'d need to communicate any changes somehow since it\'s\nnot meant to be version controlled.\n\nTo deploy, run dep deploy.\n\nIf you have any suggested improvements then I\'d love to hear them.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2016-12-14 10:12:04','1','2016-12-14 14:21:33','1','2016-12-14 10:26:21','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecbaa','0aad6165-fde3-49f5-a1cc-fab3f2cba697','slick Carousel - Hide and Show Previous / Next Buttons','slick-carousel-hide-and-show-previous-next-buttons','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"I was using the excellent [slick Carousel](http://kenwheeler.github.io/slick/) and needed to implement next and previous buttons to move the carousel in the desired direction, but also had to show and hide these buttons depending on the current slide as I didn\'t want to use the infinite functionality in this scenario.\\n\\nFirst off, initialise the plugin using your desired options, I\'d say that these are the minimum requirement but in this case I also had `arrows` set to `false`, `dots` set to `true` and was also using the `lazyLoad` option:\\n\\n```\\n$(\'.steps\').slick({\\n    infinite: false,\\n    slidesToShow: 1,\\n    slidesToScroll: 1\\n});\\n```\\n\\nThen use the slick api to move the carousel when buttons are clicked: \\n\\n```\\n$(\'.next\').click(function() {\\n    $(\'.steps\').slick(\'slickNext\');\\n});\\n\\n$(\'.previous\').click(function() {\\n    $(\'.steps\').slick(\'slickPrev\');\\n});\\n```\\n\\nand, finally:\\n\\n```\\n$(\'.steps\').on(\'beforeChange\', function(event, slick, currentSlide, nextSlide) {\\n\\n    if (nextSlide == slick.slideCount - 1) {\\n        $(\'.next\').hide();\\n        $(\'.previous\').show();\\n    } else if (nextSlide != slick.slideCount - 1 && nextSlide != 0) {\\n        $(\'.next\').show();\\n        $(\'.previous\').show();\\n    } else if (currentSlide == 0 || nextSlide == 0) {\\n        $(\'.next\').show();\\n        $(\'.previous\').hide();\\n    }\\n\\n});\\n```\\n\\nI used `beforeChange` because using the `afterChange` meant the showing and hiding didn\'t happen until what felt like to be too late, since the new slide has to be in place before that code is executed.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>I was using the excellent <a href=\"http://kenwheeler.github.io/slick/\">slick Carousel</a> and needed to implement next and previous buttons to move the carousel in the desired direction, but also had to show and hide these buttons depending on the current slide as I didn\'t want to use the infinite functionality in this scenario.</p>\n<p>First off, initialise the plugin using your desired options, I\'d say that these are the minimum requirement but in this case I also had <code>arrows</code> set to <code>false</code>, <code>dots</code> set to <code>true</code> and was also using the <code>lazyLoad</code> option:</p>\n<pre><code>$(\'.steps\').slick({\n    infinite: false,\n    slidesToShow: 1,\n    slidesToScroll: 1\n});\n</code></pre>\n<p>Then use the slick api to move the carousel when buttons are clicked:</p>\n<pre><code>$(\'.next\').click(function() {\n    $(\'.steps\').slick(\'slickNext\');\n});\n\n$(\'.previous\').click(function() {\n    $(\'.steps\').slick(\'slickPrev\');\n});\n</code></pre>\n<p>and, finally:</p>\n<pre><code>$(\'.steps\').on(\'beforeChange\', function(event, slick, currentSlide, nextSlide) {\n\n    if (nextSlide == slick.slideCount - 1) {\n        $(\'.next\').hide();\n        $(\'.previous\').show();\n    } else if (nextSlide != slick.slideCount - 1 &amp;&amp; nextSlide != 0) {\n        $(\'.next\').show();\n        $(\'.previous\').show();\n    } else if (currentSlide == 0 || nextSlide == 0) {\n        $(\'.next\').show();\n        $(\'.previous\').hide();\n    }\n\n});\n</code></pre>\n<p>I used <code>beforeChange</code> because using the <code>afterChange</code> meant the showing and hiding didn\'t happen until what felt like to be too late, since the new slide has to be in place before that code is executed.</p>\n</div>','28','I was using the excellent slick Carousel [http://kenwheeler.github.io/slick/] \nand needed to implement next and previous buttons to move the carousel in the\ndesired direction, but also had to show and hide these buttons depending on the\ncurrent slide as I didn\'t want to use the infinite functionality in this\nscenario.\n\nFirst off, initialise the plugin using your desired options, I\'d say that these\nare the minimum requirement but in this case I also had arrows  set to false, \ndots  set to true  and was also using the lazyLoad  option:\n\n$(\'.steps\').slick({\n    infinite: false,\n    slidesToShow: 1,\n    slidesToScroll: 1\n});\n\n\nThen use the slick api to move the carousel when buttons are clicked:\n\n$(\'.next\').click(function() {\n    $(\'.steps\').slick(\'slickNext\');\n});\n\n$(\'.previous\').click(function() {\n    $(\'.steps\').slick(\'slickPrev\');\n});\n\n\nand, finally:\n\n$(\'.steps\').on(\'beforeChange\', function(event, slick, currentSlide, nextSlide) {\n\n    if (nextSlide == slick.slideCount - 1) {\n        $(\'.next\').hide();\n        $(\'.previous\').show();\n    } else if (nextSlide != slick.slideCount - 1 && nextSlide != 0) {\n        $(\'.next\').show();\n        $(\'.previous\').show();\n    } else if (currentSlide == 0 || nextSlide == 0) {\n        $(\'.next\').show();\n        $(\'.previous\').hide();\n    }\n\n});\n\n\nI used beforeChange  because using the afterChange  meant the showing and hiding\ndidn\'t happen until what felt like to be too late, since the new slide has to be\nin place before that code is executed.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2017-02-27 13:04:24','1','2017-02-27 13:13:00','1','2017-02-27 13:12:32','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecbae','328edefa-c7d7-4aa9-99f3-b5db4467b157','Redirecting back to a paginated results page in Laravel','redirecting-back-to-a-paginated-results-page-in-laravel','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"Apologies if this is obvious, but thought it could possibly help others. I had this link on a product detail page to redirect back to the results page:\\n\\n```\\n<a href=\\\"{{ URL::previous() }}\\\">Search Results</a>\\n```\\n\\nbut after the page reload triggered by adding the item to the basket, that link would go \'back\' to the same page (not to mention the possibility of navigating to the page from somewhere other than the results page). I couldn\'t think of any way around it but managed to fix it by updating the controller method for the search results page. The items are fetched using the inbuilt paginator:\\n\\n```\\n\\n/* query logic */\\n\\n$items = $items->paginate(15);\\n\\n$url = $items->url($items->currentPage()); // e.g. /some-url?page=1\\n\\n// then append all the get params to the string from above\\nforeach ($request->all() as $key => $value) {\\n    $url .= \'&\' . $key . \'=\' . $value;\\n}\\n\\n$request->session()->put(\'results-route\', $url);\\n```\\n\\nthen use `<a href=\\\"{{ Session::get(\'results-route\') }}\\\">Search Results</a>` instead.\\n\\nNot sure if there\'s a neater way but chuffed I managed to come up with a solution, had no idea how I was going to fix that.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>Apologies if this is obvious, but thought it could possibly help others. I had this link on a product detail page to redirect back to the results page:</p>\n<pre><code>&lt;a href=&quot;{{ URL::previous() }}&quot;&gt;Search Results&lt;/a&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<p>but after the page reload triggered by adding the item to the basket, that link would go \'back\' to the same page (not to mention the possibility of navigating to the page from somewhere other than the results page). I couldn\'t think of any way around it but managed to fix it by updating the controller method for the search results page. The items are fetched using the inbuilt paginator:</p>\n<pre><code>\n/* query logic */\n\n$items = $items-&gt;paginate(15);\n\n$url = $items-&gt;url($items-&gt;currentPage()); // e.g. /some-url?page=1\n\n// then append all the get params to the string from above\nforeach ($request-&gt;all() as $key =&gt; $value) {\n    $url .= \'&amp;\' . $key . \'=\' . $value;\n}\n\n$request-&gt;session()-&gt;put(\'results-route\', $url);\n</code></pre>\n<p>then use <code>&lt;a href=&quot;{{ Session::get(\'results-route\') }}&quot;&gt;Search Results&lt;/a&gt;</code> instead.</p>\n<p>Not sure if there\'s a neater way but chuffed I managed to come up with a solution, had no idea how I was going to fix that.</p>\n</div>','29','Apologies if this is obvious, but thought it could possibly help others. I had\nthis link on a product detail page to redirect back to the results page:\n\n<a href=\"{{ URL::previous() }}\">Search Results</a>\n\n\nbut after the page reload triggered by adding the item to the basket, that link\nwould go \'back\' to the same page (not to mention the possibility of navigating\nto the page from somewhere other than the results page). I couldn\'t think of any\nway around it but managed to fix it by updating the controller method for the\nsearch results page. The items are fetched using the inbuilt paginator:\n\n\n/* query logic */\n\n$items = $items->paginate(15);\n\n$url = $items->url($items->currentPage()); // e.g. /some-url?page=1\n\n// then append all the get params to the string from above\nforeach ($request->all() as $key => $value) {\n    $url .= \'&\' . $key . \'=\' . $value;\n}\n\n$request->session()->put(\'results-route\', $url);\n\n\nthen use <a href=\"{{ Session::get(\'results-route\') }}\">Search Results</a> \ninstead.\n\nNot sure if there\'s a neater way but chuffed I managed to come up with a\nsolution, had no idea how I was going to fix that.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2017-03-20 15:12:32','1','2017-03-20 15:15:45','1','2017-03-20 15:15:45','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecbb2','f1b9ad74-46cb-4722-ae27-f859937648c1','How to Manually Trigger a Password Reset Email in Laravel 5','how-to-manually-trigger-a-password-reset-email-in-laravel-5','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"I\'ve been trying to figure this out for a while before I cracked it:\\n\\n**Users Controller**\\n\\n    use Illuminate\\\\Foundation\\\\Auth\\\\SendsPasswordResetEmails;\\n\\n    class Users extends Controller\\n    {\\n\\n        use SendsPasswordResetEmails;\\n  \\n        public function resetPassword(Request $request, $id)\\n        {\\n            $this->sendResetLinkEmail($request);\\n\\n            // your response\\n        }\\n\\n\\nThe form I used in my view is\\n\\n    <form id=\\\"password-reset-form\\\" action=\\\"/users/{{ $user->id }}/reset-password\\\" method=\\\"put\\\">\\n       {{ csrf_field() }}\\n       <input type=\\\"hidden\\\" name=\\\"_method\\\" value=\\\"put\\\">\\n       <input type=\\\"hidden\\\" name=\\\"email\\\" value=\\\"{{ $user->email }}\\\">\\n       <button type=\\\"submit\\\">Reset Password</button>\\n    </form>\\n\\nThen all you need is a route\\n\\n    Route::put(\'users/{id}/reset-password\', \'Users@resetPassword\');\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>I\'ve been trying to figure this out for a while before I cracked it:</p>\n<p><strong>Users Controller</strong></p>\n<pre><code>use Illuminate\\Foundation\\Auth\\SendsPasswordResetEmails;\n\nclass Users extends Controller\n{\n\n    use SendsPasswordResetEmails;\n\n    public function resetPassword(Request $request, $id)\n    {\n        $this-&gt;sendResetLinkEmail($request);\n\n        // your response\n    }\n</code></pre>\n<p>The form I used in my view is</p>\n<pre><code>&lt;form id=&quot;password-reset-form&quot; action=&quot;/users/{{ $user-&gt;id }}/reset-password&quot; method=&quot;put&quot;&gt;\n   {{ csrf_field() }}\n   &lt;input type=&quot;hidden&quot; name=&quot;_method&quot; value=&quot;put&quot;&gt;\n   &lt;input type=&quot;hidden&quot; name=&quot;email&quot; value=&quot;{{ $user-&gt;email }}&quot;&gt;\n   &lt;button type=&quot;submit&quot;&gt;Reset Password&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;/form&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Then all you need is a route</p>\n<pre><code>Route::put(\'users/{id}/reset-password\', \'Users@resetPassword\');</code></pre>\n</div>','30','I\'ve been trying to figure this out for a while before I cracked it:\n\nUsers Controller\n\nuse Illuminate\\Foundation\\Auth\\SendsPasswordResetEmails;\n\nclass Users extends Controller\n{\n\n    use SendsPasswordResetEmails;\n\n    public function resetPassword(Request $request, $id)\n    {\n        $this->sendResetLinkEmail($request);\n\n        // your response\n    }\n\n\nThe form I used in my view is\n\n<form id=\"password-reset-form\" action=\"/users/{{ $user->id }}/reset-password\" method=\"put\">\n   {{ csrf_field() }}\n   <input type=\"hidden\" name=\"_method\" value=\"put\">\n   <input type=\"hidden\" name=\"email\" value=\"{{ $user->email }}\">\n   <button type=\"submit\">Reset Password</button>\n</form>\n\n\nThen all you need is a route\n\nRoute::put(\'users/{id}/reset-password\', \'Users@resetPassword\');',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2017-04-13 16:32:07','1','2017-04-13 16:34:58','1','2017-04-13 16:34:34','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecbb4','6255194e-7ce9-4241-8cbc-5908208d0371','How to Use Laravel Echo Without npm','how-to-use','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"Just a quick post about how to use Laravel Echo without the npm package.\\n\\nThe way I did it was to add it to my local project as per the docs:\\n\\n    npm install --save laravel-echo pusher-js\\n\\nThen I copied the `node_modules/laravel-echo/dist/echo.js` file to my `public/vendor` directory.\\n\\nThen I just updated my scripts partial to include the Echo js file and the Pusher library:\\n\\n    <!-- Echo -->\\n    <script>\\n      var module = { };\\n    </script>\\n\\n    <script src=\\\"{{ cached_asset(\'vendor/echo.js\', true) }}\\\"></script>\\n\\n    <!-- Pusher -->\\n    <script src=\\\"{{ cached_asset(\'vendor/pusher.min.js\', true) }}\\\"></script>\\n\\n    <script>\\n      window.Echo = new Echo({\\n        broadcaster: \'pusher\',\\n        key: \'{{ config(\'broadcasting.connections.pusher.key\') }}\',\\n        cluster: \'eu\',\\n        encrypted: true\\n      });\\n    </script>\\n\\nThe `var module = { };` is needed because how it\'s meant to be used with webpack I think, I picked that up from a Stack Overflow answer.\\n\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>Just a quick post about how to use Laravel Echo without the npm package.</p>\n<p>The way I did it was to add it to my local project as per the docs:</p>\n<pre><code>npm install --save laravel-echo pusher-js\n</code></pre>\n<p>Then I copied the <code>node_modules/laravel-echo/dist/echo.js</code> file to my <code>public/vendor</code> directory.</p>\n<p>Then I just updated my scripts partial to include the Echo js file and the Pusher library:</p>\n<pre><code>&lt;!-- Echo --&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n  var module = { };\n&lt;/script&gt;\n\n&lt;script src=&quot;{{ cached_asset(\'vendor/echo.js\', true) }}&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n\n&lt;!-- Pusher --&gt;\n&lt;script src=&quot;{{ cached_asset(\'vendor/pusher.min.js\', true) }}&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n\n&lt;script&gt;\n  window.Echo = new Echo({\n    broadcaster: \'pusher\',\n    key: \'{{ config(\'broadcasting.connections.pusher.key\') }}\',\n    cluster: \'eu\',\n    encrypted: true\n  });\n&lt;/script&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<p>The <code>var module = { };</code> is needed because how it\'s meant to be used with webpack I think, I picked that up from a Stack Overflow answer.</p>\n</div>','31','Just a quick post about how to use Laravel Echo without the npm package.\n\nThe way I did it was to add it to my local project as per the docs:\n\nnpm install --save laravel-echo pusher-js\n\n\nThen I copied the node_modules/laravel-echo/dist/echo.js  file to my \npublic/vendor  directory.\n\nThen I just updated my scripts partial to include the Echo js file and the\nPusher library:\n\n<!-- Echo -->\n<script>\n  var module = { };\n</script>\n\n<script src=\"{{ cached_asset(\'vendor/echo.js\', true) }}\"></script>\n\n<!-- Pusher -->\n<script src=\"{{ cached_asset(\'vendor/pusher.min.js\', true) }}\"></script>\n\n<script>\n  window.Echo = new Echo({\n    broadcaster: \'pusher\',\n    key: \'{{ config(\'broadcasting.connections.pusher.key\') }}\',\n    cluster: \'eu\',\n    encrypted: true\n  });\n</script>\n\n\nThe var module = { };  is needed because how it\'s meant to be used with webpack\nI think, I picked that up from a Stack Overflow answer.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2017-04-26 11:19:00','1','2017-04-26 11:24:15','1','2017-04-26 11:23:54','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecbb8','6b94b498-424d-458e-8a9a-c4c3b0809dfe','FormData Does Not Work With PUT Requests','formdata-doest-not-work-with-put-requests','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"Save yourself the time, if you are trying to submit a form via ajax using `FormData`, it doesn\'t work with put requests, change the request type to post and it should be fine.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>Save yourself the time, if you are trying to submit a form via ajax using <code>FormData</code>, it doesn\'t work with put requests, change the request type to post and it should be fine.</p>\n</div>','32','Save yourself the time, if you are trying to submit a form via ajax using \nFormData, it doesn\'t work with put requests, change the request type to post and\nit should be fine.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2017-06-09 10:58:17','1','2018-01-23 10:05:22','1','2017-06-09 10:58:56','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5a68ea2c9c47ff40bdeecbb9','045986b7-e7df-445d-9518-43078c8cb005','Laravel 5 - Handle Old Password Hashes','laravel-5-handle-old-password-hashes','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"\\nI recently had to deal with migrating legacy systems to a Laravel 5.4 app, as you might have guessed, the legacy app was using sha1 and not bcrypt.\\n\\nHere is how I managed to silently update sha1 passwords to the more secure bcrypt version:\\n\\n```\\n<?php\\n\\nnamespace App\\\\Listeners;\\n\\nuse Illuminate\\\\Auth\\\\Events\\\\Attempting;\\nuse Illuminate\\\\Queue\\\\InteractsWithQueue;\\nuse Illuminate\\\\Contracts\\\\Queue\\\\ShouldQueue;\\n\\nuse App\\\\User;\\n\\nuse Hash;\\n\\nclass CheckOldHashedPassword\\n{\\n    /**\\n     * Create the event listener.\\n     *\\n     * @return void\\n     */\\n    public function __construct()\\n    {\\n        //\\n    }\\n\\n    /**\\n     * Handle the event.\\n     *\\n     * @param  Login  $event\\n     * @return void\\n     */\\n    public function handle(Attempting $event)\\n    {\\n        $user = User::where(\'email\', $event->credentials[\'username\'])->first();\\n\\n        if (!empty($user) && $user->password === sha1($event->credentials[\'password\'])) {\\n            // update password\\n            $user->password = Hash::make($event->credentials[\'password\']);\\n            $user->save();\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nJust created the above file in `app\\\\Listeners`.\\n\\nDepending on the name of your login field, you might need to change the array key being used in `$event->credentials`, possibly `username` or `email`.\\n\\nIf you are using md5 or something else, then you can easily add in the checks that you need.\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>I recently had to deal with migrating legacy systems to a Laravel 5.4 app, as you might have guessed, the legacy app was using sha1 and not bcrypt.</p>\n<p>Here is how I managed to silently update sha1 passwords to the more secure bcrypt version:</p>\n<pre><code>&lt;?php\n\nnamespace App\\Listeners;\n\nuse Illuminate\\Auth\\Events\\Attempting;\nuse Illuminate\\Queue\\InteractsWithQueue;\nuse Illuminate\\Contracts\\Queue\\ShouldQueue;\n\nuse App\\User;\n\nuse Hash;\n\nclass CheckOldHashedPassword\n{\n    /**\n     * Create the event listener.\n     *\n     * @return void\n     */\n    public function __construct()\n    {\n        //\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * Handle the event.\n     *\n     * @param  Login  $event\n     * @return void\n     */\n    public function handle(Attempting $event)\n    {\n        $user = User::where(\'email\', $event-&gt;credentials[\'username\'])-&gt;first();\n\n        if (!empty($user) &amp;&amp; $user-&gt;password === sha1($event-&gt;credentials[\'password\'])) {\n            // update password\n            $user-&gt;password = Hash::make($event-&gt;credentials[\'password\']);\n            $user-&gt;save();\n        }\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Just created the above file in <code>app\\Listeners</code>.</p>\n<p>Depending on the name of your login field, you might need to change the array key being used in <code>$event-&gt;credentials</code>, possibly <code>username</code> or <code>email</code>.</p>\n<p>If you are using md5 or something else, then you can easily add in the checks that you need.</p>\n</div>','33','I recently had to deal with migrating legacy systems to a Laravel 5.4 app, as\nyou might have guessed, the legacy app was using sha1 and not bcrypt.\n\nHere is how I managed to silently update sha1 passwords to the more secure\nbcrypt version:\n\n<?php\n\nnamespace App\\Listeners;\n\nuse Illuminate\\Auth\\Events\\Attempting;\nuse Illuminate\\Queue\\InteractsWithQueue;\nuse Illuminate\\Contracts\\Queue\\ShouldQueue;\n\nuse App\\User;\n\nuse Hash;\n\nclass CheckOldHashedPassword\n{\n    /**\n     * Create the event listener.\n     *\n     * @return void\n     */\n    public function __construct()\n    {\n        //\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * Handle the event.\n     *\n     * @param  Login  $event\n     * @return void\n     */\n    public function handle(Attempting $event)\n    {\n        $user = User::where(\'email\', $event->credentials[\'username\'])->first();\n\n        if (!empty($user) && $user->password === sha1($event->credentials[\'password\'])) {\n            // update password\n            $user->password = Hash::make($event->credentials[\'password\']);\n            $user->save();\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n\nJust created the above file in app\\Listeners.\n\nDepending on the name of your login field, you might need to change the array\nkey being used in $event->credentials, possibly username  or email.\n\nIf you are using md5 or something else, then you can easily add in the checks\nthat you need.',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2017-07-04 16:49:33','1','2017-07-04 16:54:17','1','2017-07-04 16:53:20','1',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
	('5b3f6db11c3361377aab682c','6e91950c-3483-4d4b-aa09-dcd316562140','Download and Import Database Backups from S3','download-and-import-database-backups-from-s3','{\"version\":\"0.3.1\",\"markups\":[],\"atoms\":[],\"cards\":[[\"card-markdown\",{\"cardName\":\"card-markdown\",\"markdown\":\"I made a [gist](https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/1cea53f840a3f124519afa57b3647a2f) which is also embedded below:\\n\\n<script src=\\\"https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/1cea53f840a3f124519afa57b3647a2f.js\\\"></script>\"}]],\"sections\":[[10,0]]}','<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>I made a <a href=\"https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/1cea53f840a3f124519afa57b3647a2f\">gist</a> which is also embedded below:</p>\n<script src=\"https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/1cea53f840a3f124519afa57b3647a2f.js\"></script></div>',NULL,'I made a gist\n[https://gist.github.com/martincarlin87/1cea53f840a3f124519afa57b3647a2f]  which\nis also embedded below:',NULL,0,0,'published',NULL,'public',NULL,NULL,'1','2018-07-06 13:25:05','1','2018-07-06 13:25:38','1','2018-07-06 13:25:38','1',NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);

